<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA -- The Angolan government is seeking urgent explanations
from the Portuguese authorities about the reasons behind the
killing of five Angolan nationals in Lisbon's "Luanda" disco gas
attack, official news agency Angop reported on Thursday. (Angola-
Portugal-Clarification)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French police said on Thursday that a separatist group
called "Brittany Revolutionary Army (ARB)" was the prime suspect
in a bomb attack on Wednesday against a McDonald's restaurant in
Brittany.
</P>
<P>
The attack, which took place near the Brittany city of Dinan,
killed a 27-year-old woman worker of the restaurant and triggered
widespread condemnation in France. (France-Bomb Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Parents of three boys who caused a train crash in
Belgium rail line on Tuesday have to pay for part of damages of
millions of Belgian francs, local media said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Three boys, aged 8, 9 and 13 respectively, have confessed that
they had put a concrete block on a crucial switch in a hope to
watch a train crash. (Belgium-Train Crash-Compensation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- The Angolan government appealed for "good sense" of
the international community in barring any foreign support to the
armed rebels led by Jonas Savimbi, the official Angop news agency
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This statement was made in New York by the country's foreign
minister Joao Miranda, at a UN Security Council meeting which
discussed the report put forward by the UN sanctions committee on
Angola. (Angola-Rebel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French Defense Minister Alain Richard and Chief of
General Staff of the French Armed Forces, General Jean-Pierre
Kelche, will visit India in the coming weeks, the French Defense
Ministry announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Richard will visit New Delhi on May 18 and 19, while Kelche
will be in India from April 23 to 27, said a spokesman of the
ministry, Jean-Francois Bureau. ( France-India-Defense)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Nineteen people were gunned down by militants in
two separate massacres in northeast India's Assam and Tripura
states on Wednesday, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a case of ethnic cleansing, 11 Nepali settlers, eight of
them from one family, were shot dead by militants of the Karbi
National Volunteer Force in Assam's hill district of Karbi Anglong
on Wednesday, the PTI quoted a local Additional Deputy Commission
L.R. Jothe as saying on telephone. (India-Militants)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- About 69 people were killed when a bus collided head-
on with a truck on Wednesday night, Kenya police said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred on the highway between the Kenyan capital
Nairobi and the Indian port city of Mombasa when people were
hurrying back to their hometown ahead of the Easter holiday,
according to police spokesman Peter Kimanthi. (Kenya-Bus Accident)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- One South Lebanon Army (SLA) militiaman was killed
and three others, including a SLA member and two Israeli soldiers,
were injured Thursday morning in south Lebanon in a series of
attacks launched by Lebanese resistance forces, Oriental Radio
station reported.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese resistance forces issued a statement in Beirut saying
that they detonated a big bomb near two Israeli positions of Abala
and Menala in south Lebanon when a Israeli patrol passed. (Lebanon-
Israeli Soldier)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's elite Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC)
on Thursday dismissed the accusation that the forces would launch
a coup d'etat against the reformists, main supporters of President
Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Issuing a statement, the IRGC said that the body which has
taken shape to safeguard the Islamic republic can never launch a
coup against its own objectives, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported. (Iran-Coup)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Former Guatemalan president and current parliament
speaker, Efrain Rios Montt, canceled a visit to France on
Wednesday for fears of treading the path of former Chilean
military leader Augusto Pinochet, Le Figaro daily reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was placed under house arrest in 1998 when he was in
Britain for medical treatment after a Spanish lawyer requested his
extradition to Spain for trial on charges of human rights abuses
during Pinochet's rule of iron fist between 1973 and 1990. (
France-Guatemala-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Heavy fighting raged in northern Sri Lanka Thursday
as Tamil Tiger rebels escalated their attacks on a government camp
amid huge losses on both sides, military officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said a battle was raging around the Iyakachchi military
base on the northernmost Jaffna peninsula with both sides
exchanging heavy artillery and mortar fires. (Sri Lanka-Fighting)
</P>
