<HEADLINE> Flooding Continues in Hungary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Flooding that raged for three
weeks in the upper reaches of the Tisza River in Hungary is now
abating, but the country did not have time to sigh a sigh of
relief as water is rising in the middle and lower reaches of the
country's second largest river.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency in Szabolcs state has been lifted, but
141 areas in six states are still in high alert.
</P>
<P>
Currently 4,465 houses are flooded or in direct danger, lots of
which have collapsed. More than 1,600 people have had to abandon
their homes, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
A total of 32,000 people are fighting with the flood. More than
8 million sand bags were used to consolidate the dams and banks of
the river.
</P>
<P>
Up to Thursday, 16 countries, including the United States,
Germany, Switzerland and other neighbor countries have provided
financial and material aids to Hungary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
