<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Mini-Summit Opens in Accra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings
warned on Thursday that unless the West Africa get further
integrated, the region will "remain weak, fragmented,
incompetitive and marginalized''.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at the opening of a mini-summit of the six out
of the 16 nations of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) in the Ghanaian capital Accra, Ghana News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Advancement of sub-regional integration through establishment
of a second monetary zone is the main focus of the meeting
attended by six presidents from Ghana, Nigeria, Guinea, Liberia,
the Gambia and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Mali president, who is the current ECOWS president, also
attended the summit as an observer.
</P>
<P>
According to a resolution of the ECOWAS summit at the end of
last year, the six countries had resolved to form the second
monetary zone by 2003 as a step toward merging with the CFA (West
African Franc) countries to forge a single monetary area covering
the whole West Africa with a population of some 250 million.
</P>
<P>
President Rawlings said the establishment of a second monetary
zone would mean the sub-region would be dealing with only two
currencies as opposed to the nine currently being used. This
would speed up the establishment of an ECOWAS Monetary Union with
a single currency by the year 2004, he added.
</P>
<P>
And to achieve the target date, a two-stage approach towards
the attainment of the convergence criteria which constitute the
bedrock of establishing the single currency has been adopted. The
primary convergence targets that have been agreed upon include:
</P>
<P>
Single digit inflation by 2004, gross foreign reserves to cover
at least three months of imports by 2000, increasing to six months
of imports by 2003 and budget deficit to be limited to 10 percent
of previous year's tax revenue by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
President Rawlings, however, said these efforts would come to
naught if issues of security and crime, especially economic, white
collar, electronic crime and money laundering are not tackled
seriously.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he suggested the establishment of an ECOWAS Criminal
 Intelligence Bureau.
</P>
<P>
He said ECOWAS hopes that by its 25th anniversary in May, it
would have made some strides and these include the opening of an
ECOWAS Court of Justice, ECOWAS Parliament and an organ to prevent
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Lansana Kouyate, Executive Secretary of ECOWAS, said
establishing a single currency for the sub-region would be
difficult. "It cannot be accomplished without difficulties but we
have to get rid of them one after the other with determination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
