<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Urges Respect of Every Nation's Right in Handling Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang
Zemin on Friday urged for consultations in handling world affairs
and called for respect of the basic right of every nation in
dealing with its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said this when criticizing the NATO war in Yugoslavia's
Kosovo province last year at a banquet hosted by Greek President
Costis Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
"A warning sent by the war is: international affairs should be
handled through consultations among nations, and the basic right
of every nation in dealing with its own internal affairs should be
respected," he said.
</P>
<P>
The war, launched a year ago by the NATO under the pretext of "
humanitarian intervention" by bypassing the U.N. Security Council,
has brought great sufferings to all the ethnic groups in Kosovo,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he added, the war, instead of settling the Kosovo
issue, has resulted in new humanitarian catastrophes and worsened
tensions in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
"Regional conflicts should be resolved through peaceful
consultations between related parties of the region," Jiang
stressed. But, he noted, "hegemonism and power politics frequently
use force to imperil regional peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the new millennium, he said, "We are gratified
to see the easing of the international situation as a whole, but
are also deeply concerned over the serious challenges facing world
peace and development."
</P>
<P>
Peace and development are the two key issues of the present
world, he noted, adding that only when the five principles of
peaceful coexistence, the purpose of the U.N. Charter and the
basic norms of other universally recognized international law are
strictly abided by, will peace be safeguarded actually and the
common development be realized.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government and people are willing to work with the
peoples of other countries to bring a peaceful and just as well as
prosperous and stable world in the 21st century, Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who arrived here Friday from Turkey for a four-day
state visit, also hailed the quick development in China and Greece,
and wanted to promote bilateral cooperation in various sectors.
</P>
<P>
In the 28 years after the establishment of diplomatic
relations between China and Greece, Jiang said, "We have respected
each other, treated each other on an equal footing, cooperated for
mutual benefit and achieved common development, thus writing a
glorious chapter in Chinese-Greek friendship."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government attaches importance to developing long-
term stable and friendly relations with Greece, and is willing to
work together with the Greek side to further expand and deepen
cooperation in political, economic and cultural fields, he
concluded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amato Named as Italian Premier-designate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian Treasury Minister and former
premier Giuliano Amato was asked by President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi
this evening to try and form a new center-left government, in the
wake of the resignation this week of Massimo D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
Ciampi gave Amato, 61, a preliminary mandate to form a new
administration to take the center-left through to the end of its
legislature, in April 2001.
</P>
<P>
Amato accepted the mandate "with reserve", meaning that he will
now have to consult with the leaders in the center-left coalition
and verify whether he can secure the parliamentary majority needed
to govern.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Premier D'Alema quit his job on Wednesday after the
center-left suffered a humiliating defeat in Sunday's regional
elections, emerging with seven regions to the center- right's
eight and polling about 45 percent of the vote against the
opposition's 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
If Amato can muster up enough support in parliament, he will
become the head of Italy's 58th post-war government.
</P>
<P>
If Amato does pass a confidence vote in both houses (the
Senate is a sure thing) he has made it plain that he wants to lead
the alliance not only through next month's electoral reform
referendum but into the next elections.
</P>
<P>
The referendum, if won, would require parliament to remove the
present 25 present of the Lower House elected proportionally,
thereby strengthening the two- party system and helping to end the
chronic instability of governments here, which are exceptionally
vulnerable to blackmailing tactics by small parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Security Council Passes New Military Doctrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 21 (Xinhua) --The Russian Security Council, the
top national security agency, approved the final text of Russia's
new military doctrine and Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin
signed it on Friday.
</P>
<P>
At a council meeting in the Kremlin, Security Council secretary
Sergei Ivanov stressed that the draft doctrine had been agreed
with all the necessary agencies and officials.
</P>
<P>
"Fundamental changes to it were not required" after the draft
was debated in February, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that changes were made only to the document's wording
to make it complete from the legal point of view.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov quoted experts as saying that the doctrine is defensive
and its main purposes are deterrence and the preservation of peace.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it firmly advocates Russia's interests in the
military sphere, he said, "the text of the military doctrine meets
Russia's national interests."
</P>
<P>
Colonel General Leonid Ivashov, chief of the Russian Defense
Ministry's Main Board for International Military Cooperation, said
after the meeting that under the new doctrine threshold of nuclear
weapon use by Russia is extremely low.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia's new military doctrine clearly determines that
the country's internal political security is provided for by
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he admitted that "undoubtedly, some
provisions of the military doctrine are to a certain extent a
response to U.S. and NATO attempts to act from a position of
strength, to build a unipolar world and to expand the geography of
the North Atlantic Alliance."
</P>
<P>
However, "Russian nuclear weapons can be used only against an
aggressor using weapons of mass destruction against Russia or in a
critical situation in the event of a large-scale aggression
against Russia," the general said.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the military doctrine and the concept of
national security, as well as the ratification of START II and the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty by the parliament, implies
that Russia is more actively searching for ways of achieving
national security and global strategic stability, he said.
