<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Flood Emergency Assistance to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has approved a
credit of 30 million U.S. dollars in response to the Mozambican
government's request for emergency assistance following floods in
the African country, the bank announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The flood emergency recovery project will help Mozambique
maintain macroeconomic stability through the financing of imports
necessary to rebuild social and economic infrastructure, and by
reestablishing production levels, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed project will be quick-disbursing and performance
will be measured by how well Mozambique maintains macroeconomic
stability in the year 2000 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be provided by the International Development
Association (IDA), the World Bank's lending arm for the poorest
countries, and on standard IDA terms of 40 years maturity,
including 10 years grace.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rains, which started in early February, continue to
disrupt several southern provinces of Mozambique, and have killed
640 persons, according to the World Bank. About 2 million people
are experiencing severe economic difficulties, including 491,000
people who are either displaced or trapped in flood-isolated areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
