<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian New Premier Giuliano Amato </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian Treasury Minister Giuliano
Amato on Friday evening was named Italy's premier-designate, to
replace outgoing leader Massimo D'Alema, who resigned on Wednesday
after eighteen months at the helm of the center-left.
</P>
<P>
Amato, 61, served as Socialist party premier from June 1992 to
April 1993, when he led Italy through a dire financial crisis, as
it rebounded from the embarrassment of the lira being forced out
of the European Monetary System.
</P>
<P>
During his premiership, he enacted the first and deepest of a
string of austerity budgets that ultimately led to Italy
confounding its critics and qualifying for European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
An academic nicknamed "Doctor Subtle" for his ability to see
the
fine points of an argument, Amato was Number Two in the Socialist
party to Bettino Craxi, who died in self-imposed exile in Tunisia
in January, a fugitive from Italian justice.
</P>
<P>
Amato's reputation was virtually unscathed by the corruption
scandals that toppled his political master and destroyed his party.
</P>
<P>
He came out of political retirement in October 1998, to head
the institutional reform ministry in the government put together
by Massimo D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
In April 1999, Amato became D'Alema's Treasury Minister,
filling the gap left by Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, who was elected
President.
</P>
<P>
Amato was born in Turin on May 13, 1938.
</P>
<P>
A graduate, like Ciampi and D'Alema, of the prestigious Normale
University in Pisa, where he took law, Amato also obtained a
master's degree in comparative law from Columbia University's
School of Law in 1962.
</P>
<P>
He joined the Socialist party in 1958 and became a member of
its central committee in 1978.
</P>
<P>
From 1964 to 1969, he taught law at the university of Rome,
before moving on to Perugia and then Florence, and returning to
Rome in 1975 to take up a post in comparative and constitutional
law, which he taught until 1994.
</P>
<P>
He was first elected to parliament in 1983 and served as
cabinet chief to Craxi from 1983 to 1987.
</P>
<P>
In 1987 he was re-elected to parliament and served as deputy
premier; from 1987 to 1989 he was Treasury minister.
</P>
<P>
From 1989 to 1992 he was deputy head of the Socialist party,
just as it began to be enmeshed in the corruption scandals that
brought down Italy's old guard.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 he was re-elected to parliament and later that year
appointed premier.
</P>
<P>
After his spell at the head of government, he returned to
academic studies as the head of Aspen Institute Italia, before
serving as Italy's first anti-trust chief from November 1994 to
November 1997, during which time he handed down a string of tough
competition rulings.
</P>
<P>
He then went back to the academic life at the European
University Institute outside Florence, before returning to the
fray as reform chief under D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
Amato has published a large number of books and articles
covering the economy and public institutions, personal liberties,
federalism, and comparative government.
</P>
<P>
He is married with two children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
