<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EAC to Speed Study on Customs Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The top decision making
body of the East African Cooperation (EAC) composed of Kenya,
Uganda and Tanzania has directed the task force on establishment
of customs union to expedite its work.
</P>
<P>
The task force is charged with exploring all options on
convergence of the common external tariffs and elimination of
internal tariffs among the member states.
</P>
<P>
In a one-day EAC tripartite commission meeting held in northern
 Tanzanian town of Arusha on Thursday, it was also agreed to hold
an extraordinary meeting on June 29-30 to receive the task force's
report and give further guidance to its work.
</P>
<P>
According to an EAC press release issued on Friday, the
commission has also directed a study be undertaken to design a
mechanism for monitoring of non-tariff barriers for cross-border
trade.
</P>
<P>
Under the EAC treaty signed last November, the three partner
states have resolved to establish a customs union within four
years.
</P>
<P>
The member states also agreed to remove all the existing
non-tariff barriers on the importation of goods originating from
other partner states and refrain from imposing any further
non-tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Thursday's meeting, the new chairman of the EAC
tripartite commission Nicolas Biwott urged member states to make
rapid implementation of the decisions already taken by the
re-launched regional organization.
</P>
<P>
"Rapid implementation of the decisions taken within the
regional framework should become the hallmark of the new regional
organization as we move into the future," stressed Biwott, who is
also Kenya's Minister for Tourism, Trade and Industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
