<HEADLINE> Silver Nose-dives on Weak Global Advices in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Silver prices nose-dived by 120
rupees (2.79 U.S. dollars) a kilogram on the bullion market in
Mumbai (Bombay) Friday due to weak global advices while gold
declined on poor demand.
</P>
<P>
Ready silver (.999 fineness) showed a sharp fall of 120 rupees
(2.79 dollars) at 8,000 rupees (186.05 dollars) per kilogram from
previous close of 8,120 rupees (188.84 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Raw silver (.916 fineness) declined by 145 rupees ( 3.37
dollars) to 7,855 rupees (182.67 dollars) per kg. from previous
close of 8,000 rupees (186.04 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, standard gold close at 4,460 rupees (103.72 dollars)
per 10 grams, revealing a loss of 15 rupees (0.35 U.S. dollar)
over the last close of 4,475 rupees (104.07 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two-carat gold was nominally quoted weak at 4,125 rupees
(95.93 dollars) per 10 grams from 4,140 rupees (96.28 dollars).
</P>
