<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5.2-Magnitude Tremor Jolts West Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 5.2 degrees
on the Richter scale hit Honaz of the Denizli Province in western
Turkey's Aegean region Friday afternoon, reported the Anatolia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Istanbul-based Bogazici University Kandilli
Observatory Seismology Center made the announcement to the press
following the quake at 1523 local time (1223 GMT). No report of
damage was available.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the center, two minor tremors shook
Bandirma township of the Balikesir province, also in the Aegean
region, in the past 24 hours
</P>
<P>
The first quake was recorded at 23:02 local time (2001 GMT)
Thursday and the second at 06:12 local time (0312 GMT) the
following day. The two tremors were measured 2.6 and 2.8 degrees on
the Richter scale respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Honaz tremor is believed to be one of the largest
earthquakes following last year's two major quakes which
respectively measured 7.4 and 7.2 magnitude on Richter Scale in
northwestern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
