<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Thai Main Opposition Party Heads for Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The New Aspiration Party (NAP),
the biggest Thai opposition Party, is now heading towards a major
reshuffle as both the party leader and its secretary general
announced they will submit their resignations to the party's
executive committee on April 30, analyst here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, leader of the NAP and a former Prime
Minister, who announced his resignation on Thursday, told
reporters Friday that political movements within and outside the
NAP have been anticipated, and the move will lead to "better
politics."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a separate interview, the NAP secretary general
Chaturon Chaisaeng said that he is also resigning from the current
post.
</P>
<P>
"When the party leader resigns, the other party executives
should resign as well, in order to give a free choice to the out-
going leader to nominate members for the party's top positions,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The NAP used to hold 124 posts in the 385-member Lower House of
the Thai Parliament and is still the biggest opposition party.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the NAP lost nearly 30 parliamentary posts
to the Thai Rak Thai Party, which is under the leadership of
telecommunications tycoon Thaksin Shinawatr.
</P>
<P>
More recently, another three NAP lawmakers were reported "
likely to defect" to the Thai Rak Thai Party.
</P>
<P>
There is also a reported conflict between NAP Secretary
Chaturon and Deputy Leader Chalerm Yubamrung over the nomination
of Chalerm's sons, Art-harn and Wanchalerm, to contest in the
forthcoming general election.
</P>
<P>
NAP Executive Committee members were divided over the issue.
The majority of the executive committee were in support of Chalerm
' sons, while a few objected to the nomination.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the resignation announcement by Chavalit is
likely a political strategy to cool down the "concealed" conflicts
within the party, as well as get rid of "undesirable elements" of
the party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
