<HEADLINE> Politics in Court to Erode People's Confidence in Judiciary: Chief Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Chief Justice Latifur Rahman
Friday urged lawyers to help keep the court out of the purview of
politics, saying the entrance of politics in the arena of
judiciary would erode people's confidence in judiciary.
</P>
<P>
"If politics enters the arena of the court, justice will be
disrupted, dignity of court will be affected, and people will lose
their trust in the judiciary," he said while speaking at the
Bangladesh Bar Council conference, which was also joined by Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina said at the conference that people expect the
trial of the killers of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, the first Prime
Minister of Bangladesh, to be completed in normal course of law
for the sake of justice and rule of law in the country.,
</P>
<P>
She said for more than two decades, the killers of Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman were provided state protection and awarded with
overseas postings to represent the country abroad despite their "
proud self-confessions."
</P>
<P>
Top leaders of the ruling Awami League recently blasted the
higher judiciary for what they said delaying the process of
execution of death sentences of the killers of Sheikh Mujibur
Rahman.
</P>
<P>
While the four-party opposition alliance led by Bangladesh
Nationalist Party alleged that the criticism of judges by ruling
party leaders was designed to "destroy the judiciary." They staged
a country-wide demonstration to protest it and to further
consolidate their unity to unseat the government and establish
what they termed a "nationalist and democratic one."  
</P>
</TEXT>
