<HEADLINE> Belgian Trains Stop for Memory of Crash Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Railway personnel in Belgium
observed a work stoppage Friday to commemorate the victims of a
train disaster that occurred Tuesday near Charleroi, a southern
Belgian city.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions in Belgium called for the 30-minute memorial this
morning. An engine operator was killed after his train derailed
and collided head-on with an oncoming train. Dozens of passengers
were injured.
</P>
<P>
The accident was reportedly caused by three children who put a
concrete block on the rail. The children have been taken into
custodial care.
</P>
<P>
The damages could run up to over 100 million Belgian francs (
some 2.5 million U.S. dollars), according to a rough estimate. The
concerned parties are discussing who should pay the damages.
</P>
<P>
Consumer rights organization Test Aankoop/Test Achats urged
insurance companies to be obliged by law to cover the entire
amount of a damage caused by a minor no matter how serious, and
even if inflicted on purpose.
</P>
<P>
At present, the limit for a family policy is 35 million Belgian
francs (833,000 U.S. dollars) for material damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
