<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Duma Ratifies Nuclear Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma, lower
house of parliament, Friday overwhelmingly ratified the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) by a vote of 298-74
with three abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The voting was held behind closed doors, and by law at least
226 votes in the 450-seat Duma were needed for the approval of the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
After the voting, presidential spokesman in the State Duma
Alexander Kotenkov told reporters that the Communist faction's
amendment to the treaty was not even voted on, as it did not
correspond with the law on international treaties.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Communist faction, deputy Alexander Shabanov
demanded that a passage be included in the text to the effect
that Russia will not hand the ratification charter over to the
United Nations before the treaty is ratified by other nuclear
states.
</P>
<P>
The treaty will come into force only after the last of its
participants, including the U.S., Russia, France, Britain, China,
India, Pakistan and other nuke-potential states, hands its
ratification charter to the UN, said Kotenkov.
</P>
<P>
The United States, who has the world's largest and most
advanced nuclear arsenal, has not approved the CTBT. The U.S.
Senate rejected it in late 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ratification of the CTBT came one week after the
Duma approved the START II nuclear arms reduction pact with the
United States. Under START II, Russia and the United States will
significantly reduce the number of their nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the two important treaties are seen as
victories for Russian president-elect Vladimir Putin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
