<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's Major Landslide Rare in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 21 (Xinhua)-- The landslide that took place in
Nyingchi Prefecture in Southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region
on April 9 is the biggest China has seen and also a rare
phenomenon in the world, said experts.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters went to the site of the landslide in Bomi County on
April 18 and concluded that the landslide, which lasted about ten
minutes, occurred because the mountain slope had been heavily
soaked with melting snow due to warmer climate in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The experts said that the landslide, that piled up 60 meters
high in average over an area of about five square kilometers,
consisted mainly sand and heavily eroded stone blocks.
</P>
<P>
The landslide covered highways linking two villages and a tea
plantation, trapping 4,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The region has historically been beset with numerous landslides.
The last one occurred at the beginning of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
They ruled out any major landslides in the region in the near
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
