<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Bank to Issue Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bank for Investment and
Development of Vietnam (BIDV) on Thursday announced its plan to
issue 2,500 billion Vietnamese dong (VND) (about 178.6 million U.S.
dollars) worth of bonds from April 24, according to a report of
Vietnam News Agency (VNA) Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bank hopes to sell part of the bonds as stock commodities
on Vietnam's first stock market, set to open next July.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to open our convertible bonds to the general public
and might later put that on the stock market," VNA quoted an
official of BIDV as saying.
</P>
<P>
Final touches are currently being made for the July opening of
two stock exchange centers, one in Hanoi and another in Ho Chi
Minh City, according to the State Securities Commission (SSC) of
the country.
</P>
<P>
BIDV's new convertible bonds, which will mature over five years,
will cover registered bonds, bearer bonds and book-entry bonds
with four face values of 5 million VND, 10 million VND, 500 U.S.
dollars and 1,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bond buyers will be paid an annual interest of 6.55 percent for
Vietnamese dong bonds and 5.2 percent for U.S. dollar bonds. From
the second year, annual interest will be paid on June 26, BIDV
says.
</P>
<P>
BIDV management says it will use raised medium- and long-term
capital to fund key socio-economic projects in Vietnam, such as
the Trans-Vietnam Ho Chi Minh highway and the Na Duong Thermal
Power Plant in the northern Quang Ninh province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
