<HEADLINE> McDonald's Condemns Blast in French Restaurant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The McDonald's fast food chain
restaurant on Friday condemned the bombing attack against one of
its restaurants in Brittany, western France, in which one woman
employee was killed.
</P>
<P>
Denis Hennequin, the president of McDonald's in France, said
the restaurant has become "a favorable target" of attack by people
opposed to globalization.
</P>
<P>
"I think that this time they have jumped over the line. I dare
to hope that it would serve at the same time as a call for a
little more of calm and a little more of reason," he said in an
interview with Europe 1 television channel.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is not McDonald's fault to become a symbol of
globalization and the people who are working for the restaurant
should be respected.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to express a feeling of anger and disgust (about
the bombing)," said Hennequin.
</P>
<P>
The restaurant in Quevert which was attacked on Wednesday will
be closed on Saturday during the funeral of Laurence Turbec, who
was killed by the explosion when she was working at a drive-by
shop of the restaurant, he said.
</P>
<P>
French police suspect that the attack was made by a pro-
independence militant group in Brittany -- the Brittany
Revolutionary Army.
</P>
<P>
An anti-globalization peasant leader in France has condemned
the attack and denied any involvement. 
</P>
