<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hostility Toward Iran Never Changes: Iranian Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Seyyed Ali
Khamenei has warned that the United States has never abandoned its
hostile policy on Iran although it has softened its tone toward
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency on Friday, the leader
said that Washington's soft tone does not mean that it has given up
its intentions of political and cultural hegemony in Iran, but it
is solely a change of strategy for achieving the same oppressive
goals.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, Washington had been theorizing and
defending the so-called policy and idea of "globalization," by
which the Americans meant the global rule of the U.S. government
and a forced submission to America by other countries in Africa,
Asia, and Latin America, he said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a large gathering of young people on Thursday,
Khamenei pointed out that none of the problems of Iran would ever
be solved as a result of establishing any type of relations with
Washington, Iran's archenemy.
</P>
<P>
The Americans are more concerned about their own interests than
the interests of the governments and nations with which they dealt,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Washington and any foreign enemies of Iran would
never be able to pressure the Islamic government into any form of
submission to or reconciliation with the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
If the Americans or other enemies of the Islamic republic should
eventually be tempted to try the most extreme form of that pressure
on Iran, the result would be a crucial (armed) confrontation, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei also criticized the freedom of the Iranian press to
question the religious sanctity of many principles. He warned "some
elements" in the press against writing things against Islamic
values and becoming tools of Iran's enemies.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic and economic relations between Iran and the U.S. were
shattered when Islamic fundamentalist revolutionaries overthrew the
U.S.-backed Shah in 1979, seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and
held 52 Americans hostage for 444 days.
</P>
<P>
Since moderate President Mohammad Khatami came to power in 1997,
however, the two countries have softened their hostile tones toward
each other, even opening their doors for unofficial contacts.
</P>
<P>
Last month, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced
that Iran would be allowed to export its three major non-oil
products - carpets, pistachios and caviar - to the U.S., which was
considered the most substantial good-will step Washington has taken
toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
But there is still a long way to go before the two countries can
fully resume relations because the conservative hardliners in Iran,
who are controlling the regime, are strongly opposed to such a
move.
</P>
<P>
Washington, too, lacks trust in Iran, insisting that it supports
international terrorism, tries to obtain weapons of mass
destruction and hinders the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Iran's conservatives intensified their struggle against
reformers after they were defeated completely in February's
sensitive parliamentary elections by reformers.
</P>
<P>
One important strategy of the conservatives is to stir up
people's anti-U.S. feelings and accuse reformers of collaborating
with Iran's enemies in plotting to subvert the Islamic system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Announces Policy Framework for Stockbroking Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Securities
Commission (SC) Friday announced the Policy Framework for
Stockbroking Industry and the Reduction of Transaction Costs,
which provide a set of strategies aimed at promoting consolidation
among local stockbroking companies by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The current freeze on the issuance of new licenses for
stockbroking will continue until the objective of industry
consolidation has been achieved, the SC said in a statement to
announce the policy framework.
</P>
<P>
Under the framework, there would not be more than 15 universal
brokers in Malaysia, each of which should comprise a group of at
least four existing stockbroking companies, it said.
</P>
<P>
It said that there is obviously a need to consolidate the
stockbroking industry and the objective of consolidation is to
strengthen the industry and form a group of well-capitalised
domestic stockbroking companies which can provide efficient and
cost-effective intermediation for investors.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy framework, stockbroking companies will be
allowed to find their own merger partners and their firm merger
agreements should be executed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The SC said that a stockbroking company which could not enter
into such merger agreements by December 31, 2000 should not expect
its license to be renewed.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of the consolidation exercise, every
stockbroking company is required to have a minimum paid-up capital
of 250 million ringgit (65.789 million U.S. dollars), core capital
of at least 250 million ringgit (65.789 million U.S. dollars) and
a capital adequacy ratio of at least 1.50 times, it said.
</P>
<P>
Stockbroking companies are also required to satisfy
quantitative and qualitative criteria, which would include good
governance standards and management capabilities and also to
satisfy the necessary criteria of the SC.
</P>
<P>
All stockbroking companies which have been given firm
agreements for the merger by December 31, 2000, will be granted
tax credits for accumulated losses carried forward, and stamp duty
and real property gains tax exemptions as announced in the Year
2000 Budget on October 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
A universal broker will be allowed to offer the full range of
capital market services, it said, adding immediately upon meeting
the above criteria, a stockbroking company that has requisite
personnel will be allowed to take on corporate finance work, and
trade derivative products, and it will be allowed to undertake
additional business activities in the future, which include
managing private debt securities, trading in fixed income products
and other financial instruments as and when introduced.
</P>
<P>
A universal broker would be given latitude to open branches
throughout the country from January 1, 2002, subject to the SC's
approval.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that to enable a stockbroking company to
operate under a single license for both the equity and derivatives
markets, amendments would be made to the Securities Industry Act
1983 and the Futures Industry Act 1993.
</P>
<P>
It said a task force to be chaired by the Ministry of Finance
and comprising representatives from the SC and the KLSE will be
set up to review the status and extent of broker consolidation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Verbal Agreement on Temporary Cease-fire Issued in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Following meetings with the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), a verbal agreement on a
temporary cease-fire for the 1-3 May round of polio immunization
has been issued by the Taliban Militia and its opposition, the
Northern Alliance ,according to a press release from the office of
the UN Coordinator for Afghanistan here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a positive step, now we hope that these commitments
will be met," said the Afghanistan UNICEF Representative, Louis-
Georges Arsenault.
</P>
<P>
Close to 4.5 million Afghan children less than 5 years old may
be vaccinated against polio in this year's first anti-polio
campaign if they can be reached with the vaccine. "If every single
child under five can be vaccinated now and in future immunization
campaigns, we can rid Afghanistan of polio," said the WHO
Representative M.A. Jama.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan and Pakistan are two of the world's thirty
countries where polio continues to cripple people, mostly young
children. In Afghanistan in 1999, 156 new polio cases were
identified, which may be only a fraction of the total number
because reports did not come from all the districts.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is now awaiting the written confirmation
from both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
