<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Mini-Summit Adopts Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Six West African states outside
the franc zone of the African Financial Community Thursday night
adopted a communique with a strong commitment to creating a second
monetary union in the sub- region by January 2003, Ghana News
Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, which was available Friday morning,
presidents or their representatives from Ghana, Gambia, Guinea,
Liberia, Nigeria and Sierra Leone said the union would be launched
after all the convergence criteria laid by the 22nd ECOWAS summit
last year are met.
</P>
<P>
The 22nd ECOWAS summit held last December in Togo's capital
Lome decided on a fast-track approach to ensure an accelerated
implementation of integration programs in member countries where
conditions are mature.
</P>
<P>
The criteria include an inflation rate of not more than nine
percent by the year 2000 and five percent by 2003, a gross
external reserves to cover at least three months of imports by the
end of this year, and six months by the end of 2003.
</P>
<P>
They also include a central bank financing of budget deficit
not more than 10 percent of previous year's tax revenue, with the
percentage of budget deficit (excluding grants) to gross domestic
product not more than five percent by 2000 and four percent by
2002.
</P>
<P>
To accommodate the monetary and fiscal pressures on individual
national economies, the six countries agreed to establish an
appropriate regional compensation and stabilization arrangement
dubbed "Accra Declaration on Second Monetary Zone", the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
Modalities for implementation would involve the adoption of
"the recommendations of the Convergence Council, including the
attached Action Plan, which outlines the program of activities to
be undertaken in four stages ending in December 2002, to be
followed by the commencement of the second monetary zone in
January 2003."
</P>
<P>
"Institutional arrangements to be made include the
establishment of a Summit of Heads of State and Government;
Convergence Council of Ministers and Governors of Central Banks;
Technical Committee assisted by the Task Force; and a Common
Central Bank," according to the document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
