<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Fully Control Territorial Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda is to fully control its
territorial airspace by ensuring general alert and surveillance
through the use of a long range capacity radar installed at Rebero
hill near Kigali, Rwanda News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda has been solely dependent on monitoring done by the
Tanzanian Civil Aviation Authority in Dar es Salaam for any
aircraft flying beyond 25, 000 feet above sea level above Rwandan
territory," the report quoted Rwandan newly President-elect Paul
Kagame as saying in his project launching ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that there is critical need for the
country to have its own air traffic control and air space
surveillance system to ensure safe and efficient traffic flow.
</P>
<P>
This project would serve to bolster up the confidence of air
companies and boost the flow of air transport in the land-locked
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador of the United States to Rwanda George Staples hailed
the project, noting that "given Rwanda's strategic position on the
African continent and her potential for development, there is
great need for such modern means of technology in air traffic
control."
</P>
<P>
To increase efficiency and systems utilization, the radar will
have a remote control tower with full communication data links
between Kanombe Airport and Rebero radar site on the outskirts of
Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The first plane landed in Rwanda in 1936. Rwanda joined the
International Civil Aviation in 1964. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
