<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Li Huangxi, Self-Taught Senior Technician in China's Largest Automaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- When China's First Auto Work (
FAW) began introducing production line technology from foreign
countries in 1989, Li Huangxi was one of the many FAW maintenance
workers puzzled by the new systems and could not read manuals in
foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
Now, Li is one of the most highly-skilled technicians and a
leading experts of foreign machines in FAW, after spending days
and nights at his "home lab."
</P>
<P>
Li, now 50, is a senior technician at FAW and has been named
this year's winner of the "May Day Labor Award", a national honor
for people who have made notable contributions to the country.
</P>
<P>
Without higher education, the man lacked the confidence to
learn on his own everything necessary, which might be traced back
to the years he spent in the countryside as a "re-educated youth"
since 1968.
</P>
<P>
All his painstaking efforts began with the FAW's imported
production lines in 1989 when he turned his home into a "lab" just
for studying the imported equipment.
</P>
<P>
He spent all his savings, 2,100 yuan (about 250 U.S. dollars),
to purchase a cheap computer for setting up his "Family Computer
System" which includes a tape-recorder and a black-white TV set.
</P>
<P>
With the help of his family, his wife and their only boy, Li
got familiar with all the programs of the imported computer-
control machines.
</P>
<P>
The maintenance worker is now seen as a "magic doctor" of
foreign equipment by his colleagues at the FAW which is located in
Changchun, the capital of northeastern Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Li's intelligence has helped his company save a great deal of
money, through successfully repairing foreign machines and
replacing worn-out foreign parts with home-made ones.
</P>
<P>
Besides working in his home lab, Li has attended numerous part-
time schools and high-level training courses on electrical
equipment. "I could only become an illiterate man in front of
foreign equipment, if I don't keep learning," he says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
