<HEADLINE> Australian PM Leaves for Visits to Turkey, France, Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard left
Friday for a two-week trip to Turkey, France and Israel,
Australian Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
In Turkey, he will attend an Anzac Day commemoration at
Gallipoli along with New Zealand Prime Minister Helen Clark to
mark the 85 anniversary of a landing campaign in 1915 in which
more than 11,000 Australian and New Zealand soldiers were killed.
</P>
<P>
They will open a new memorial at Gallipoli.
</P>
<P>
The Australian and New Zealand Corps Day, Anzac Day falls on
next Tuesday and it is the de facto national day of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Howard will hold trade talks with Turkey's president and prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
In France, Howard will make a pilgrimage to the World War I
battlefields of the Somme in France, where he will make the first
bilateral contact between an Australian prime minister and a
French president since 1991.
</P>
<P>
In Israel, He plans to raise the issue of compensation for
Australians involved in the Maccabiah Bridge disaster with the
Israeli government. The bridge collapse killed four Australian
athletes and injured scores of others during the opening ceremony
of the 1997 Maccabiah Games.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"It's opportune in Israel to of course make contact with the
leadership of the Palestinian movement as the peace process
between Israel and the Palestinians has progressed very rapidly
although there is still much to be done," Howard said before
departure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
