<HEADLINE> W. African Leaders at ECOWAS Mini-Summit Support Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Seven heads of state of the
Economic Community of the West African States (ECOWAS) at a
one-day mini-summit in Ghanaian capital Accra on Thursday
expressed optimism over the sub-region' s integration process.
</P>
<P>
"We have taken a giant leap forward, and I am believer in the
adage better late than never" said Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo late Thursday night, quoted by The Ghana News Agency on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Presidents from Ghana, Nigeria, Guinea, Mali and delegations
from Liberia, Sierra Leone and the Gambia attended the one-day
summit. The plan to establish a second monetary zone by 2003
outside the current CFA Franc area is the focus of the summit.
</P>
<P>
He advised that the private sector and civil society be made to
play an active role in the integration of the economies of the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
"It takes the collective desire of our people to make this
dream a reality. They should be able to move, trade and live as
one people in such a way that they can contribute to the wealth
creation within the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
President Alpha Konare of Mali, who attended the meeting as the
current ECOWAS chairman, said that "I have the conviction that
day by day ECOWAS is growing, with the firm political will that
we have, we will achieve a lot".
</P>
<P>
"If we move individually it will take us a long time to be
strong but collectively we will become strong in no time,"
President Lassana Conte of Guinea said.
</P>
<P>
He said apart from the fact that his nation has the structures
to support such program "one currency is a powerful tool for
integration that must be supported." 
</P>
</TEXT>
