<HEADLINE> China, Mexico to Exchange Treasures Exposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China and Mexico are expected to
exchange treasures expositions later this year, according to a
letter of intent signed recently between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent says that China will hold an exposition of
the Terra-Cotta Warriors unearthed in the late 1970s from the
Mausoleum of Qin Shihuang, the first emperor of the Qin Dynasty (
221 B.C.-207 B.C.) in some major cities in Mexico later this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mexico will hold expositions of the Maya
civilization in Beijing, Xi'an and other Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent was signed between China's State
Administration of Cultural Heritage and Mexico's National
Commission of Culture and Arts.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), met with Director Rafael Tovar of Mexico'
s National Commission of Culture and Arts today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
