<HEADLINE> China to Take Leaps in Scientific Developments: Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China will try to catch up with
developed countries in economic strength by taking leaps in its
scientific developments in the 21st century, according to the
latest issue of Outlook, the country's most authoritative news
weekly.
</P>
<P>
The magazine will carry an article in its April 24 edition,
discussing weather China has the ability to take such giant
strides and what the country should do to achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
Some experts in scientific and technological strategies pointed
out that developing countries may have the chance to join
developed countries in some high-tech fields which produce new
inventions every three to five years.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, it is hoped that China will develop its
science and technology in an open, practical and market-oriented
way, according to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
However, the scientific progress should be made on the basis of
scientific and technological innovation, said Hu Angang, an
economist with the National Situation Research Center under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences and Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
He said that the market should play an active role in promoting
the scientific development, and enterprises should take a leading
role while the task for the government is to create a better
environment for such development.
</P>
<P>
The process for the country's technological leaps should
involve the entire industry and focus on key projects, especially
those in the frontier fields in the 21st century such as computer
software, information and pharmaceutical industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
