<HEADLINE> China to be Promising Market for Thai Fruits After WTO Entry: Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Exports of Thai fruits to China
are expected to increase after Beijing's entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO), the Thai Agriculture and Cooperatives
Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
China will become a promising market for Thai fruits,
particularly longans, after it was admitted to the world trade
body, given its tremendous consumer base and shorter transport
distance compared with other key overseas markets, Thailand News
Agency quoted a report of the ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government will, however, urge the Chinese side to
reduce import tariff from the current 50 percent to a lower level
to increase export volume, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The department of agriculture extension and export promotion is
also working on boosting exports of Thai fruits to other key
markets, including the United States, the European Union and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East is viewed as another promising market for Thai
fruits.
</P>
<P>
The report also urges local farmers and exporters to improve
the quality of their products and marketing management to maintain
the country's competitiveness in the international market, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
