<HEADLINE> Thai Bureaucrats Ordered to Go Native in Dress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
has imposed a dress code on bureaucrats nationwide through Thai
Interior Minister Banyat Bantadtan, The Nation newspaper disclosed
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan was quoted as saying that he had told Banyat to ensure
that bureaucrats in all regions wore local costumes on at least
one working day each week.
</P>
<P>
"This will help create jobs in clothing industry locally and
make officials feel more comfortable," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to The Nation, in the northern Thai provinces of
Chiang Rai, Mae Hong Son and Chiang Mai, wearing local folk
costume to work on Fridays has been a common practice among
bureaucrats there for some time.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that during the Songkran festival, Chiang
Mai officials were asked to wear folk costume to work all week.
</P>
<P>
In the northeastern provinces of Khon Kaen and Ubon Ratchathani
officials wear local costume to work on Fridays and in Udon Thani
on Wednesdays, it said.
</P>
<P>
It said Bangkok's bureaucrats tend to wear silk dress on any
workday of the week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
