<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Publishes Positive Economic Program for Next 15 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government Thursday
published a positive economic program for the coming 15 years,
giving optimistic prospects for national economy.
</P>
<P>
The program worked out by the Russian Economy Ministry sets a 4.
5-percent growth of the gross domestic product (GDP) for next year.
</P>
<P>
During the period from 2001 to 2003, the government will seek
to deepen structural reform and bring the transitional period to
an end, said the Russian government's Information Department.
</P>
<P>
The program targets an average annual GDP growth of over 4.5
percent for this period and a real personal income up by 25
percent compared with 1999.
</P>
<P>
In 2001, Russia's GDP will grow 4-4.5 percent, industrial
production will rise 5 percent and agricultural output 3 percent,
while capital investment will rise 6 percent and real disposable
personal incomes 5 percent, according to the program.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth will reach 6 percent in 2003 and industrial
production is expected to rise by 7-8 percent annually, it says.
</P>
<P>
The program expects the Central Bank's key refinancing rate to
drop to 20 percent by the end of 2000 and to 10-13 percent by 2003,
forecasting inflation at 10 percent next year, 8 percent in 2002
and 7 percent in 2003.
</P>
<P>
In 2001-2003, the exchange rate of the Russian ruble against
the U.S. dollar will be controlled 15-20 percent lower than
inflation, and the average exchange rate of the ruble will be 35
rubles for one dollar in 2001, predicted Russian Economy Minister
Andrei Shapovalyants.
</P>
<P>
Such a difference between the ruble exchange rate and dynamics
of the consumer price index would be favorable for economic
development in the next few years, he said.
</P>
<P>
The price of Russian oil on the world market will be maintained
at about 18 U.S. dollars per barrel in 2001-2003, Shapovalyants
believes.
</P>
<P>
The increase of Russia's annual oil output to 300-308 million
tons is "positive" and an annual gas production of 600-610 billion
cubic meters will be good for preventing a deficiency of that fuel,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It would be good for the Russian economy to increase oil
production to 350 million tons next year," he noted, adding that
Russia will not cut exports of raw materials in the next two or
three years and the domestic need for raw materials will also go
up.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to stimulate investment, including
creating an insurance agency to attract investment and forming a
pool of banks to investment in the real sector of the economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the program, the priority of the second phase of
the development strategy -- from 2004 to 2007 -- will be to attain
maximum economic growth rates of at least 6 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the third stage -- from 2008 to 2015 -- will be long-
term economic stability, with steady growth and constant renewal
of the technological and production structures of the economy.
</P>
<P>
However, government officials said that that is an optimistic
prediction.
</P>
<P>
A report placed by Shapovalyants on the government's website
said: "According to the second version of the prognosis, when the
influence of unfavorable factors and the accomplishment of
existing threats are possible, higher inflation figures and lower
GDP growth may happen."
</P>
<P>
But Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin told a government
session Thursday that "we have better figures now than ones
forecast for 2001," because "GDP rose by 8 percent in the first
quarter of this year, which is not just steady growth, but also a
rapid growth."
</P>
<P>
Russia's industry has been undoubtedly developing according to
the encouraging scenario since the beginning of the year.
Nevertheless, observers say that the country's economy has not
recovered by far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Arrives in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
arrived here Friday for a state visit to Greece at the invitation
of Greek President Costis Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
This is the first visit of the Chinese president to the country.
During the visit, Jiang is expected to exchange views with
Stephanopoulos and other Greek leaders on bilateral ties and major
international and regional issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Jiang and his wife, Wang Yeping, were greeted at the airport by
Greek Minister of Justice Michalis Stathopoulos and Ambassador to
China Ioannis Theophanopoulos. Chinese Ambassador to Greece Zhen
Jianguo and embassy staff were also at the airport.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement distributed at the airport, Jiang said
that his present visit is aimed at deepening understanding,
furthering friendship and expanding cooperation between China and
Greece.
</P>
<P>
"I believe, with the joint efforts of the two countries, the
visit will turn out to be a great success," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China and Greece are both ancient countries with
splendid culture, and have made significant contributions to the
human civilization and social progress. The peoples of the two
countries have also enjoyed long history of friendship, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed that China treasures the Sino-Greek friendship,
and the recent years have witnessed enhanced development of the
bilateral cooperation in the fields of politics, economy, culture
as well as science and technology.
</P>
<P>
China will spare no efforts to consolidate the bilateral long-
term and stable cooperation oriented towards the 21st century, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's entourage arriving on the same special plane include
Vice Premier Qian Qichen and his wife, State Councilor Wu Yi,
Director of the General Office of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC)
Central Committee Wang Gang, Minister in charge of the State
Development Planning Commission Zeng Peiyan, Director of the
Policy Research Office of CPC Central Committee Teng Wensheng,
Vice Foreign Minister Ji Peiding, Vice Director of the General
Office of the CPC Central Committee and Director of the Central
Guards Bureau You Xigui, Vice Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Sun Guangxiang, Special Assistant Wang Huning
and Director of President Jiang's office Jia Ting'an.
</P>
<P>
Greece is the fourth leg of Jiang's five-nation tour of Asia,
Europe and Africa, which has brought him to Israel, Palestine and
Turkey, and will take him to South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
