<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet to Build Over 100 Towns to Accelerate Urbanization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Tibet Autonomous
Region plans to build 100 small towns along its major highways to
accelerate the region's urbanization.
</P>
<P>
The decision comes at a time when sociologists and reformers
are calling for expanded urbanization which they believe will push
forward the region's economy.
</P>
<P>
In the past 50 years, Tibet has set up 112 towns, according to
Xu Mingyang, the region's deputy chairman. But urbanization at
present remains only at 9.8 percent and infrastructure conditions
in many towns still lag far behind other regions.
</P>
<P>
Urbanization, or building cities, is a global trend, and the
regional government views it an effective way to develop its
economy and to narrow its gap with the prosperous coastal areas,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
So Tibet wants to take advantage of the opportunity created by
the ongoing national drive to develop western China and to build
100 new towns along the Qinghai-Tibetan Highway, Sichuan-Tibetan
Highway and China-Nepal Highway in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
By 2006, the region will be able to supply 60 percent of its
county town residents with liquefied natural gas, he said.
</P>
<P>
By 2008, it will solve the heating problems for most of its
urban residents; and by 2010, Tibet will renovate 80 percent of
the housing of its county towns and border trading ports and
increase its urbanization to 22 percent, with the total urban
population reaching 780,000, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qingdao City to Build New Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China's noted coastal city
Qingdao in Shandong Province will open up 12 square kilometers in
the eastern part to build a new town.
</P>
<P>
The project is another strategy of the city government to
promote local economic development in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Named Fushan New Town, the 12-square-kilometer town will
provide home to 250,000 citizens. It will be the largest
residential district of Qingdao City.
</P>
<P>
The city has mobilized experts to draft overall planning for
the development of the new town and urged them to take into
account natural and human environment, industrial setups and
living facilities.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao is now collecting design schemes from six noted urban
planning and design institutes in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
