<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Central Bank Protects Pound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Central Bank of Lebanon has stepped
in to support the Lebanese pound this week after U.S. dollars
almost disappeared from the market and security fears increased,
Daily Star newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted dealers as saying that the bank has provided
almost all of the 63 million dollars demanded this week. Last week
it supplied around 70 percent of the 40-million-dollar market.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeing capital shifting toward the dollar", said Habib
Haddad, head of treasury at the Beirut Riyad Bank. "The regional
situation and to a smaller degree public finances are causing a
little pressure."
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank intervened last week for the first time in
almost a year to support the pound, which weakened on fading hopes
of a peace agreement to accompany a planned Israeli troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
The interbank exchange rate remained at 1,514 Lebanese pounds to
one dollar this week, the top of the Central Bank's intervention
band. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
