<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qingdao to Hold Ocean Science Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The coastal city of Qingdao in
east China's Shandong Province is to hold an international forum
on the relationship between ocean science and technology and
economic growth in late July.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 Qingdao International Forum of Ocean Sci-Tech and
Economic Development will hold discussions on oceanic resources
and sustained development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is jointly sponsored by the Ministry of Land and
Resources, the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the China Association
of Science and Technology, the National Bureau of Oceanography and
the Qingdao Municipal Government.
</P>
<P>
Academic exchanges at the forum will focus on ocean resources
and the impact of economic development on the environment, the
administration of the coastal region and framework of policies and
regulations, according to the organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 academicians of the Chinese Academy of Sciences
along with over 200 experts and scholars from Japan, the United
States, the Republic of Korea, Russia, Hong Kong, Taiwan and other
countries and regions will attend.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao is an ocean town with 6,000 scientists and specialists
engaging in scientific research, teaching and management,
accounting for 40 percent of China's total ocean experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
