<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Coalition for Missing Israeli Soldiers has
set up a three-man committee to investigate a report indicating
that the three MIAs from the Sultan Yakoub battle are buried in a
neighboring Arab country.
</P>
<P>
Yona Baumel, whose son Zachary went missing in the June 1982
battle along with comrades Zvi Feldman and Yehuda Katz, said the
families demand that the report, which appears Friday on the
Nazaretzh-based A-Sinara newspaper, be checked thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a "well informed" high-ranking Palestinian
official who knows a source claiming to have information on the
burial site, which he is willing to divulge for money.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat would be taking a tough line
in his meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington, Arab
sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was scheduled for late Thursday night, Israel time.
Arafat met U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright at her
Georgetown home and was to go to the White House later.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Minister of State for Non-government Organization
Hassan Asfour said on Tuesday that he saw little hope for any
breakthrough during the summit.
</P>
<P>
A second week of Israeli-Palestinian talks ended at Bolling Air
Force Base in Washington last weekend with an exchange of position
papers, but no evidence of significant progress. Clinton met
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak last week and has been taking a
more active mediating role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Three Israel Defense Forces soldiers of the Golani Brigade
were lightly wounded by shrapnel Thursday when a bomb planted by
Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas next to the security fence on the
Lebanese border exploded.
</P>
<P>
In other incidents, a soldier of the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army and two Hezbollah guerrillas were killed.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, an Israeli commando unit killed two
Hezbollah guerrillas who were on their way out of the security zone
in an encounter in the zone's central sector. The soldiers waylaid
a Hezbollah squad in an ambush, and no one was hurt on the Israeli
side.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Panathinaikos Athens of Greece beat Maccabi Tel Aviv of
Israel by 73-61 in front of a crowd of adoring Greek fans in
Salonika, thus winning the European Basketball Championship League
final.
</P>
<P>
The loss ends a fantastic Maccabi season that put Israeli
basketball back on the map in Europe and rekindled interest at
home, causing fans to camp out overnight and pay six times face
value for tickets.
</P>
<P>
In Tel Aviv's Rabin Square, the shouts of thousands of fans that
gathered to watch the game on an enormous screen turned from
excitement and anticipation to disappointment. By the end of the
game the outcome was clear from the downcast face and quiet
grumbling of fans streaming out of the square. 
</P>
</TEXT>
