<HEADLINE> hke042113--Pakistan Pledges to Eradicate Poppy Crop This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A Pakistani anti-narcotics
official said Friday that Pakistan has fulfilled its international
commitment to eradicate production of the poppy crop in the
country by bringing it to the level of almost zero.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Narcotics Division Muhammad Aziz Khan said there
is only a minor spot in Khyber agency where the poppy crop is
still being cultivated and the government is determined to wash
out this menace in total this year.
</P>
<P>
"We have succeeded in doing away with the production of poppy
and are confident of achieving zero level poppy cultivation by the
end of the year 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a success story, because Pakistan will no longer be a
drug-producing country," he said, adding that his country "is
taking all possible steps" to control drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, is constantly in touch with international
agencies to extend all possible cooperation to effectively deal
with the problem.
</P>
<P>
The international agencies must take notice of the inflow of
drugs from Afghanistan, which is affecting all the neighboring
countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Ruling Party Attacks Western Favor of Zanzibar Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's ruling party
Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) has accused the western countries of
interfering in the country's internal affairs by siding with the
trouble-making opposition party Civic United Front (CUF) in
Zanzibar, local media reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A statement of the CCM Central Committee, read by its
Secretary-General Phillip Mangula on Thursday, warned the western
countries to prepare to share the blame if the on-going unrest in
the spice islands ends in bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
The party also expressed its "shock and disappointment" at the
western countries' complaints that CCM and the Zanzibar
Revolutionary Government had failed to implement the
Commonwealth-brokered agreement with the CUF.
</P>
<P>
The statement was released during a CCM Central Committee
meeting held on Wednesday in Zanzibar and presided over by CCM
national chairman Benjamin Mkapa, who is also the president of the
east African country.
</P>
<P>
"The constant threats of an eye for an eye, a tooth for a tooth
and a nose for nose by the CUF will not be tolerated," Mangula
said at the CCM office in Dar es Salaam, accusing the West of
keeping silent even when the CUF provoked violence in a bid to
destroy bilateral understanding.
</P>
<P>
Mangula also played a video tape showing CUF leaders uttering
what he described as "dangerous words".
</P>
<P>
In the 10-minute tape, CUF Secretary-General Seif Shariff Hamad
was shown calling for a policy of "an aye for an eye" at a public
rally, and CUF Vice Chairman Shaaban Mloo urging his supporters
"not wait to be given machetes (a kind of farm chopper)".
</P>
<P>
Other CUF leaders also warned that a "bloody civil uprising"
could soon come into being in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
According to Mangula, the CCM and the Zanzibar government last
week attempted to implement the agreement through a bill for
constitutional amendment through the House of Representatives, but
the move was blocked by CUF legislators.
</P>
<P>
Since January when the Zanzibar treason trial came for hearing,
Zanzibar has been frequently hit by riots as CUF supporters and
policemen were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the then Secretary-General of the Commonwealth
Secretariat, Chief Emeka Anyaoku, expressed his disappointment at
the failure of the CCM and the Zanzibar government to implement
the agreed memorandum.
</P>
<P>
On April 6, the European Union mission in Dar es Salaam issued
a statement pressuring the Tanzanian government to intervene in
the Zanzibar treason case before the October general elections.
</P>
<P>
"If the current situation in Zanzibar continues, this will have
a negative impact on the international community's perception of
human rights, good governance and democracy in the United Republic
of Tanzania," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On April 12, police in Zanzibar arrested more than 60 people in
 connection with the recent disturbance which involved
law-enforcers and the CUF members.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar Revolutionary Government has flatly rejected pleas
of amnesty for the 18 CUF activists facing treason charges.
</P>
<P>
The first arrests in the treason case were made at the end of
November 1997 on the eve of an important by-election in Mkunazini,
Zanzibar, which the CUF nevertheless won.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen CUF members and supporters were charged with sedition,
but the next month the charge was changed to conspiracy to commit
treason, which is a non-bailable offence and carries a mandatory
life or death sentence under Zanzibar laws.
</P>
<P>
Over the following months, four more CUF members were charged
with the same offence on allegations of conspiring to topple
Zanzibar President and the revolutionary government.
</P>
<P>
All the 18 treason suspects, who have been languishing in the
Kiinua Miguu prison for more than two years, had pleaded not
guilty to the treason charges.
</P>
<P>
The first hearing of the case was held on January 19 which saw
fierce clashes between police and rioters, with at least 29 people
including 14 policemen injured and hospitalized and some 40 others
arrested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
