<HEADLINE> Zambia Cleans Up Illegal Firearms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
embarked on an operation to clean up illegal arms in townships all
over the country, the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa has directed police to
start a clean-up exercise in houses suspected to harbor illegal
firearms, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview on Thursday, Machungwa said that his ministry
would use any method possible to recover firearms.
</P>
<P>
"If we suspect that some houses have illegal weapons, we will
conduct a search," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would not allow criminals to threaten
the resuscitation of the economy and the growth of democratic
principles and good governance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a pass-out parade for police recruits in
Lusaka, Machungwa said it was his ministry's intention to acquire
helicopters for the police to improve the ability and agility to
fight crime.
</P>
<P>
There could not be any meaningful economic investment in the
country if the safety of the investors and their investment were
not secured, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said policing in the country has become extremely dangerous
because criminals used military firearms against people.
</P>
<P>
He called on police officers to use all the necessary force to
deal with dangerous criminals while upholding the human rights of
citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
