<HEADLINE> World Bank Releases 35 Million U.S. Dollars for Ugandan Primary Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has released 35
million U.S.

dollars to Uganda to support the country's primary education, the
New Vision, a leading newspaper in Uganda, reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Francis Xavier Lubanga, permanent secretary of the Ministry of
Education and Sports, announced that the fund was in fulfillment
of one of the key effective conditionalities of the World Bank
toward the implementation of the Universal Primary Education (UPE)
program in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a workshop to prepare Resident District
Commissioners (RDCs) to carry out a survey on primary teachers'
payroll and give them an update on developments in primary
education.
</P>
<P>
The money will be ready this May and will be used for the
recruitment of teachers, pay their salaries and for classrooms
construction, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lubanga assured the RDCs that it is the government's policy to
ensure that all teachers who were appropriately appointed and
posted are on the payroll and receive their salaries before or
around 28th of every month.
</P>
<P>
Uganda launched UPE program in January 1997, when the primary
school enrolment registered 2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
The enrolment has hit 6.5 million with the implementation of
UPE program over the past two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
