<HEADLINE> Nikkei Index Plunges to 15-Week Closing Low in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The benchmark Nikkei index plunged
to a 15-week closing low in Tokyo Friday, hit by a selling spree
relating to next Monday's reshuffle of the index's components.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined 706.64 points, or 3.
73 percent, from Thursday's close to end at 18,252.68, the lowest
closing since January 7.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX) which covers
all First Section issues, however, rose 5.12 points, or 0.31
percent, to 1,634.12.
</P>
<P>
The key index opened higher, helped by an upturn in high-priced
information and technology issues, but plunged rapidly in the
afternoon, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Issues to be removed from and to be included in the Nikkei
index drew both bargain-hunting and profit-taking following their
recent rapid movements, making the key index fluctuate violently
in the afternoon, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section expanded to 1,119.24 million
shares from Thursday's 692.06 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Several issues to be removed from the key index plunged to
record lows, while those to be added in the index hit record highs.
</P>
<P>
Information and high-tech issues were generally higher,
reflecting firmness on Wall Street and the U.S. dollar's advance
to the upper 105 yen range, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Retailers, chemical firms and brokerage houses remained firm,
while real estate firms, paper makers and rubber makers posted
large declines.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers 968 to 306, with 106 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
