<HEADLINE> China to Build Technological Development Centers in Major Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China will build technological
development centers in all its key enterprises before the end of
the year, a Chinese official has pledged.
</P>
<P>
Wang Wanbin, deputy minister of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, made the promise during a recent national meeting on
techno-innovations in enterprises held in Nanning, capital of
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Wang explained the move is meant to promote technical progress
in Chinese enterprises and to upgrade industrial technology in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Only 221 Chinese enterprises now have state-certified
technological development centers, accounting for 74 percent of
the country's key enterprises, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting agreed that creation of a
technological innovation information network will be the first
step in extending the new system to medium-sized and small
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The network will include a vast store of information on
scientific achievements as well as difficult technical problems in
enterprises, namelists of qualified personnel, and brand-name
commodities for sale.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2001, websites on techno-innovation information
will be opened in all the municipalities, provincial capitals, and
major cities in China, Wang added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
