<HEADLINE> African Leaders to Meet Over Zimbabwe's Land Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
will meet Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano, Namibian
President Sam Nujoma and South African President Thabo Mbeki over
the situation prevailing in the country regarding the land issue.
</P>
<P>
The four leaders are expected to meet in Zimbabwe on Friday
after a summit of the belligerents in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) in the resort town of Victoria Falls.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Presidential Spokesman George Charamba Thursday said
Mbeki and Chissano had been approached by the British government
to help restore communication between Harare and London following
differences over land, which have seen Zimbabwean war veterans
occupy nearly 1,000 white-owned farms countrywide.
</P>
<P>
"What the president has decided to do is to brief his
colleagues," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Violence has broken out at some of the farms, resulting in the
death of two white farmers, while several war veterans have been
injured or are missing.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the war veterans and the white commercial
farmers met on Wednesday in an effort to quell the violence,
resolve their differences and find an amicable solution to the
problem. They are expected to meet again next week.
</P>
<P>
The differences between Britain and Zimbabwe over the land
issue worsened after the Parliament of Zimbabwe recently passed
the Constitutional Amendment Bill, which empowers the government
to compulsorily acquire land and compel the British government to
pay compensation.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo has offered to help narrow
the differences between Zimbabwe and its former colonial master
Britain over the land issue.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo brokered a meeting between Mugabe and British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook on the sidelines of the European Union
(EU)-Africa summit in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader, through his Foreign Minister Sule Lamido,
sent a special message for Mugabe concerning the land issue on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe is also expected to host an informal meeting on the DRC,
which is to be attended by Nujoma, Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan President
Paul Kagame in Victoria Falls, Charamba said.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the leaders are expected to work
out a plan for the pull-out of foreign forces in the DRC after the
arrival of 5,000 U. N. peacekeeping forces that are expected to be
deployed around mid-year.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia have troops fighting alongside the
DRC army against those from Rwanda and Uganda who are supporting
rebels trying to topple the government of DRC President Laurent
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
During the recent EU-Africa summit in Cairo, Museveni asked
Mugabe to invite all the belligerents in the DRC to meet to work
out and agree on a timetable for the pull-out, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"It is an informal meeting and whatever deliberations from the
meeting will then be formally presented to Zambian President
Frederick Chiluba as Chairman of the DRC peace process," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
