<HEADLINE> Kenya's Coffee Prices Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's coffee prices were firm
at this week's auction in the capital Nairobi although poorer
qualities were sold at lower prices, the East African Standard
newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The market was a little quiet with reduced activity at the
Tuesday auction because of Easter, traders said.
</P>
<P>
At the auction, AA grade fetched 95 to 199 U.S. dollars per
50-kilogram bag from 97 to 177 U.S. dollars last week and PB
grade sold at 81 to 130 U. S. dollars per bag compared with 89 to
121 U.S. dollars last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, AB grade was sold at 65 to 151 U.S. dollars per bag
from 69 to 140 U.S. dollars last week and T grade eased to 38 to
79 U.S. dollars per bag from 54 to 80 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi Coffee Exchange said it sold 40,273 bags of coffee
out of the 40,855 bags offered for sale, adding that it will
offer over 40,000 bags at the auction to be held next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that coffee production in Nyeri District in
central Kenya, one of the country's major coffee producers, has
increased to 62 million kilograms as against the previous season's
35.1 million kilograms, a record increase of 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
Favorable weather conditions and availability of farm inputs
were the major forces behind the improved coffee production, local
officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
