<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Government Fails to Spur Cotton Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite efforts taken by
the Tanzanian government to simulate cotton development, the
production of this major cash crop in the east African country has
been declining, the Business Times reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cotton output in this season has dropped to 200,000 bales,
while that in 1997/98 and 1998/99 seasons were 379,087 bales and
201,400 bales respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Cotton Lint and Seeds Board had estimated to
export about 250,000 bales this season. However, due to the low
production this season, that target cannot be attained, leaving a
shortfall of about 50,000 bales, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives said the decline
in cotton production is associated with many factors including the
poor agricultural inputs due to the low purchasing power of
farmers.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to arrest the decline, the government directed the
cotton board to introduce a development fund to help farmers solve
money problems.
</P>
<P>
Money for the fund is to be drawn from cotton buyers within and
outside the country. Exporters are supposed to contribute to the
fund before exporting the commodity, while internal buyers make
monthly contributions.
</P>
<P>
However, the money being paid by the fund to farmers cannot
offset their production costs, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
