<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Reports 23-Percent Profit Growth Despite Light PC Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corp., already
embattled in an antitrust case with the federal government and 19
states, Thursday reported a 23-percent profit growth for its third
quarter, according to reports from the company.
</P>
<P>
That profit beats Wall Street estimates by 2 cents a share
despite what the world's biggest software company said was light
demand for business PCs in the period.
</P>
<P>
The Redmond, Washington-based giant said net profits for the
three months ending March 31 rose to 2.39 billion U.S. dollars, or
43 cents a share, compared to 1.91 billion dollars, or 35 cents a
share, in the same quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The company, which makes the Windows operating system found on
about 80 percent of personal computers, had been expected to earn
41 cents a share, according to consensus analyst estimates
compiled by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
Revenues for the three months rose to 5.66 billion dollars from
4.6 billion dollars a year earlier, but the company said sales to
computer makers were hit by a slowdown in demand for business PCs
early in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
Geographically, Microsoft saw the strongest improvement in Asia,
where an economic recovery powered 44-percent growth in sales, to
709 million dollars. Sales in the South Pacific and Americas
region grew 32 percent to 2.02 billion dollars while in Europe,
the Middle East and Africa rose 28 percent to 1.26 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This is pretty weak," said J.P. Morgan analyst William
Epifanio. "I expected much higher sales than this, even with the Y
2K bug effects in the last quarter."
</P>
<P>
Epifanio and other analysts say the new Windows 2000 operating
system, designed for corporate networks and work stations, will
help boost sales in the company's fiscal year 2001, which starts
July 1. Windows 2000 was introduced February 17, though most
corporations who might purchase it will take their time in testing
and installing the new software.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft shares were hit hard this month after a federal
judge's antitrust ruling against the company on April 3. U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled that Microsoft
violated antitrust law by illegally using its monopoly power. The
case stemmed from a lawsuit filed by the Justice Department and 19
states.
</P>
<P>
Since March 31, when the stock closed at 106.25 dollars,
Microsoft has plummeted more than 25 percent, contributing to a
major market selloff and investor uncertainty that continues to
linger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
