<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Korea Institute for Industrial
Economics and Trade has readjusted South Korea's gross national
product (GDP) growth for this year up to 7.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a report issued Friday, the government-run think tank said
it raised the GDP growth up by 0.8 percentage points from its
original projection of 6.5 percent based on recovery in domestic
consumption and booming exports along with inventory buildup.
</P>
<P>
It also forecast growth of 6.4 percent in private consumption
and a rise of 5.6 percent in consumption expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Fixed investment is expected to grow 26.7 percent due to
improved corporate financial structure, booming exports and
increasing new venture businesses.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, exports are projected to expand 22.7 percent
to 176.3 billion U.S. dollars and imports 38.2 percent to 165.5
billion dollars with a trade surplus of 10.8 billion dollars,
which is down from original 13.9 billion. 
