<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sumitomo, Sakura to Move up Merger by One Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan's two major commercial banks,
Sumitomo Bank and Sakura Bank, have agreed to move up the date of
their planned merger by one year to April 1 2001, the two banks
announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
By doing so, the two banks hope to remain competitive amid a
rush of consolidation and reorganization in Japan's banking
industry, officials of the banks said.
</P>
<P>
The Sumitomo business group and the Mitsui group, to which
Sakura Bank belongs, will name the new company Sumitomo Mitsui
Banking Corp., the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo Bank President Yoshifumi Nishikawa will become
president of the new bank, while Sakura Bank President Akishige
Okada will become chairman.
</P>
<P>
The two banks announced last October that they would merge by
April 2002.
</P>
<P>
Japan's banking industry will soon be reorganized into four
major banking groups.
</P>
<P>
Since the Sumitomo-Sakura merger announcement last October, two
other banking groups, one involving Sanwa Bank, Tokai Bank and
Asahi Bank and the other comprising the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi
and Mitsubishi Trust &AMP; Banking Corp., have announced mergers
scheduled for April 2001.
</P>
<P>
Last August, three other major Japanese banks, the Industrial
Bank of Japan, Fuji Bank and Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, revealed a plan
to integrate their operations to create Mizuho Financial Group
this September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
