<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart Bypass Surgery On-Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Web surfers can now watch the
entire heart bypass surgery operation performed at the Fuwai
Hospital attached to the Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences,
China's top cardiovascular surgery hospital .
</P>
<P>
This will be the first live on-line telecast of heart bypass
surgery in China.
</P>
<P>
Lin Kejian, a 57-year-old retired worker from Beijing's
suburban Shunyi District, will be the patient undergoing the three
to four hours heart bypass procedure.
</P>
<P>
Lin suffered three heart attacks in the past six months, and
doctors at Fuwai Hospital say heart bypass surgery is the best
treatment for him.
</P>
<P>
Wu Qingyu, vice president of the hospital who will perform the
surgery, said that by accessing: www.cctv.com or www.bta.net.cn,
Internet users can learn more details about heart disease.
</P>
<P>
Today's Beijing Daily quoted the doctor as saying that coronary
heart disease has become the number one killer in the world, and
it is especially a threat to older people. However, prevention
and early treatment of the disease can help save lives.
</P>
<P>
He said that many people do not know much about cardiac surgery,
and are afraid of undergoing the operation because they believe it
is risky and very expensive.
</P>
<P>
Wu added that some patients miss the crucial time to undergoing
cardiac surgery, sometimes with fatal consequences.
</P>
<P>
He said coronary artery bypassing surgery is now a routine
procedure at his hospital, and the success rate has reached 99
percent.
</P>
<P>
Wu said he himself has performed some 700 coronary artery
bypass operations, once conducting three in one day.
</P>
<P>
Fuwai Hospital also has a telephone hotline for those who want
to ask questions about this operation. The phone numbers are
68330774 and 68330225. 
</P>
</TEXT>
