<HEADLINE> Original Yuan Renminbi Attracts Collectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The original version of the yuan
renminbi, China's currency, has aroused the interest of an
increasing number of collectors.
</P>
<P>
At a recent auction held by Shanghai International Commodity
Auction Ltd., 35 notes and coins of the version were all auctioned
off.
</P>
<P>
Of these, a 50-yuan-note with the picture of a bridge on the
front side was sold for 5,000 yuan (about 602 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A source with the company said that old versions of the yuan
have been selling well in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The rarity of the original version has been pushing its price
higher and higher, the source said.
</P>
<P>
This first edition of the yuan was in circulation between 1948
and 1953, and bulk of its notes and coins are no longer available
now because of a lack of collectors at that time.
</P>
<P>
China issued the fifth version of the yuan renminbi last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
