<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks Report Lower Losses, Small Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Thai banks are reporting lower
net losses and small profits for the first quarter as banking
analysts predict brighter prospects for the whole sector this year,
local newspaper the Nation reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Leading the turnaround is Siam Commercial Bank (SCB), which
reported a first quarter net profit of 609 million baht (16.24
million U.S. dollars) against a loss of 222.4 million baht (5.93
million dollars) in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
It was the third consecutive quarter that the bank has been
profitable.
</P>
<P>
The result did not surprise analysts because the bank has
already set aside full provisions for loan losses.
</P>
<P>
The net profit mainly came from an increase in net interest and
dividend income, which the bank attributed to its debt
restructuring and the settlement of problem loans.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Asia also reported 211.27 million baht (5.6 million
dollars) net profits in the first quarter, compared with a loss of
175.63 million baht (4.68 million dollars) in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
DBS Thai Danu Bank announced a drop in net losses in the first
quarter to 174.7 million baht (4.65 million dollars) compared to a
loss of 347.3 million baht (9.98 million dollars) in the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Nakornthon Bank also showed a much improved
first quarter result, with net losses down sharply from 410.73
million baht (10.95 million dollars) in the first quarter of last
year to 165.21 million baht (4.4 million dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
However, Bangkok Bank, the country's largest commercial bank,
is expected to post further losses due to heavy loan provisioning
last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
