<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PSA Fails to Bring Crimes Down in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite the enactment of the
controversial Public Safety Act (PSA) two months ago, the criminal
activities were increasing throughout the country, The Independent
newspaper Friday quoted the quarterly report of the Coordinating
Council for Human Rights in Bangladesh as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said that after the enactment of the PSA, a total of
189 persons were murdered in February and 263 in March.
</P>
<P>
The number of women killed in February was 27, and this figure
rose to 65 in March, the reported said.
</P>
<P>
The report said 135 women and children were raped across the
country between January and March. Among the rape victims, 26 died.
</P>
<P>
A total of 179 persons were killed in different road accidents
throughout the country in February, and the figure increased to
293 in March, the report revealed.
</P>
<P>
The incidents of rape, acid throwing, dowry, suicide, theft,
snatching and looting increased in March compared to February.
Looting incidents in February totaled 24, but they rose to 141 in
March, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested 1,655 persons on various charges in February
and 1,736 in March, the reported said.
</P>
<P>
The controversial PSA was passed by Bangladeshi Parliament on
January 30, aiming at improving the law and order situation by
curbing certain crimes which disturb peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
