<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Arafat Hold Talks on Mideast Peace  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Thursday he hoped Israel and the Palestinians could bridge their
differences so that a framework accord could be reached in May,
thus smoothing the way toward a final agreement in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders held a three-hour meeting at the White House
and Washington will take on "a more intensified role" at the
request of the Israeli and Palestinian leaders, according to a
White House official.
</P>
<P>
The official said the Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will
resume peace talks on the Middle East later this month. The last
round of talks ended last weekend at Bolling Air Force Base near
Washington without any progress on narrowing gaps over a series of
issues like borders, Jerusalem, refugees and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Before his talks with Arafat, Clinton told reporters at the
White House that he noted the "risks and difficulties" for a final
peace agreement between the two sides, but said he hoped they
could be bridged.
</P>
<P>
he said the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations "reached a very
serious time in the peace process," and he would work hard along
with Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
"He and Prime Minister Ehud Barak have set for themselves an
ambitious timetable to reach a framework agreement as soon as they
can and then a final agreement by the middle of September. so we
are working hard on it, and I think we'll get some things done
today," Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this afternoon, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
met Arafat at her Georgetown residence. State Department spokesman
James Rubin did not disclose anything about their discussions at a
regular briefing, saying he was not aware of any new U.S. ideas
being presented, but he did not rule out the possibility of "
creative suggestions" at some points.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that the United States was prepared to play a more
active role in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations as the
September deadline for a final status agreement was drawing nearer.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone is agreed that we will play a more involved role by
being at the table, trying to be creative, trying to help each
side figure out what its needs are," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would do whatever he could to help bridge the
gap between Israel and the Palestinians over a series of issues,
like the borders, Jerusalem, refugees and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Bill Clinton
wanted to use the face-to-face talks to make sure what Washington
could do to help Israeli-Palestinian negotiations move toward a
framework agreement and then a final status agreement.
</P>
<P>
"I think the president thought it would be useful and effective
to use this time to meet directly to see what we can do to keep
these (talks) on track," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Clinton held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Barak
to try to renew momentum in the negotiations between Israel and
the Palestinians as the target date for a framework agreement in
May was drawing nearer while gaps still remained wide between the
two parties.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said both Israel and the Palestinians were facing very
difficult issues, saying that "they have a very tight time line."
</P>
<P>
The second round of Bolling Air Force Base negotiations between
Israeli and the Palestinian delegations ended last weekend with an
exchange of position papers on the framework agreement but no
evidence of substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials say that Washington is trying to help bridge the
gaps but it has not reached the stage of proposing compromises.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said Monday that he would take some "positive ideas" to
the White House, and considered his trip to Washington "a crucial
and basic step to push the peace process forward."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian cabinet minister Hassan Asfour Tuesday held out
little hope for a breakthrough when Arafat met Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We have nothing new to add, he said. "There is no place for
more flexibility. We were the party which made a historical
concession in 1993 and not the Israelis."
</P>
<P>
The year of 1993 was the year of the Oslo accords between
Israel and the PLO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
