<HEADLINE> Myanmar newspaper Calls for Measures in Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Official newspaper The New Light
of Myanmar Friday called for taking remedial measures in the trade
sector for the betterment of Myanmar's economy after Asian nations
including Myanmar were hit by the economic turmoil which began in
mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
"Myanmar's foreign trade was also affected to a certain degree.
Another factor is the imposing of economic sanctions on Myanmar by
some big Western nations which led to blockades in national
economic progress," the paper said in an article.
</P>
<P>
The paper suggested some remedial measures to be taken for the
purpose which include: to pave way for the national entrepreneurs
to extend business and for the state to receive the tax revenues
as projected, to publicly announce the trade rules and procedures,
to effectively render services, to conduct organizational reforms
and work efficiency courses to bring about skilled personnel in
the services; to reform current trade laws.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's foreign trade,
including the border trade, amounted to 3.5889 billion U.S.
dollars in 1999, falling by 8.98 percent compared with 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
