<HEADLINE> Ukraine Asks U.S. to Extradite Ex-premier for Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine expects the United States to
extradite former prime minister Pavel Lazarenko as soon as
possible to face criminal investigations, said Ukrainian
Prosecutor-General Mikhail Potebeniko Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the presidential committee for
fighting corruption and organized crime, Potebeniko said that
Ukraine had received guarantee from U.S. to bring back Lazarenko,
who was accused by the country's procuratorate on charge of money-
laundering, abusing power and corruption.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko would be extradited via Switzerland if U.S. couldn't
extradite him directly to Ukraine, the Prosecutor-General said.
</P>
<P>
Potebeniko also denied west media reports that Ukraine didn't
want Lazarenko back after he was detained by U.S. police in April
last year.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko, 45, led Ukraine's government in 1996-97. He is
suspected of stealing 2.1 million U.S dollars of government money
and illegally stashing about 4 million dollars in a Swiss bank
between 1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
In February 1999, Lazarenko fled to the United States and
applied for political asylum after being stripped of his
legislative immunity and served with an arrest warrant at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
