<HEADLINE> Hubei Boosts Pharmaceutical Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The output value of pharmaceutical
industry in central China's Hubei Province is expected to reach 10.
3 billion yuan this year, up 12 percent over 1999.
</P>
<P>
The industrial added value will be 3.1 billion yuan, up 10
percent; and the sales value will come to 8.27 billion yuan,
against 5.68 billion yuan in 1999, said an official of the local
pharmaceutical department.
</P>
<P>
Hubei has 119 pharmaceutical enterprises and 20 medical
instruments and apparatus plants. According to local statistics,
its drug consumption is around 3.5 billion yuan a year, with an
annual rise of about five percent.
</P>
<P>
Its pharmaceutical industry takes the lead in the country in R&AMP;
D. Its output of amino acid and hormones ranks first in China.
The province has set up a number of pharmaceutical production
bases for vitamins, hormones, children' drugs and medicine related
to ophthalmology, and quality TCM materials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Suffers Severe Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Hubei Province in central China is
suffering its most severe drought in half a century.
</P>
<P>
More than 980 reservoirs in the province have reported alarming
drops in water levels. And so far, almost one million people and
749,000 heads of livestock in several cities in northern part of
the province are facing a severe drinking water shortage.
</P>
<P>
The water level in Danjiangkou, the largest reservoir on the
Hanjiang River, a major tributary which flows into China's longest
river, the Yangtze River, has dropped to 135.31 meters, lower than
the normal yearly average historically.
</P>
<P>
The province has had a small amount of rainfall since the start
of this year. According to the weather forecast by the Provincial
Meteorological Bureau, the seasonal drought will continue for some
time.
</P>
<P>
Some 45 million yuan (5.4 million US dollars) worth of
government funding has been in place and millions of manpower
mobilized to fight against the natural disaster, which has
temporarily eases the drinking water shortage for 280,000 local
residents and 230,000 livestock.
</P>
<P>
However, some 560,000 ha. of farmland in the province has been
severely damaged due to the lack of irrigation water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hastens Three Gorges Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The government of Chongqing has
decided to invest 45 billion yuan (5.4 billion U.S. dollars) to
build a highway network in upcoming four or five year.
</P>
<P>
Half of the highway network will cover the dam areas of the
Three Gorges Water-Control Project.
</P>
<P>
Relocation of residents living in the dam areas is part of the
smooth construction of the gigantic Three Gorges Power Project,
the largest of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
As the construction of Three Gorges Dam has entered the second
stage, about 100,000 residents are required to move out of the dam
areas in each of the next 10 years. Shanghai and 10 provinces in
eastern China promise to receive the settlement of 70,000 migrants.
</P>
<P>
To help ensure the relocated people's life and production, the
building of more than 15 million sq. m. of houses is underway,
along with the construction of 684 km of roads, 2,260 km of power
transmission lines and 3,312 km of telecommunications lines.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government of Chongqing invested 400 million
yuan (48.1 million U.S. dollars) to build 820 km of roads linking
resettlement villages with the municipal highway network. New
roads with a total length of 350 km will be built this year. A
highway network connecting all the resettlement villages is
expected to be set up by 2001, said Li Jian, deputy director of
the Chongqing Municipal Communications Department.
</P>
<P>
As 164 primary and secondary schools at six counties in Wanzhou
Prefecture will be submerged during the second phase of the dam
construction, the local government will allocate 500 million yuan
(60 million U.S. dollars) to move 88 schools to other parts of the
prefecture this year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Wanzhou has moved 91 schools, 60 newly built schools
have been put to use. Relocation of schools have cost the
government a total of 250 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of the gigantic Three Gorges Project in 2009,
over 1.3 million residents shall have been resettled, including
those from Hubei Province and Chongqing Municipality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
