<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New e-Wave Bringing about Wireless Information  Society </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A new e-wave is bringing about
the much-expected wireless information society driven by the
greater convergence of communications and information technologies.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Economic Development Board Chairman Philip Yeo has
recently said that "communications industry itself envisions a
world with seamless wireless connection, with access to
information anywhere, anytime."
</P>
<P>
He said wireless technology infrastructure and wireless
content are two key factors that drive the growth of wireless
business and the development of solutions and services will help
deliver both the contents and the infrastructure to form a
wireless information society.
</P>
<P>
Rapid proliferation of mobile phones as well as other hand-
held devices like personal assistants (PDAs) and quick adoption of
new technologies that allows handphones to access the Internet is
greatly boosting the potential in the wireless market and setting
off a new upsurge of e-wave.
</P>
<P>
Handphone users have outstripped personal computer users by
450 million to 150 million globally and recent studies have
projected that the number of global mobile users will reach one
billion by 2003, a figure testifying to the prediction that there
will be more non-PC devices accessing the Internet than PCs by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, there are some 1.4 million mobile-phone users
out of its 3.8 million residents.
</P>
<P>
Wireless Application Protocol (WAP) technology, as the key
technology cornerstones, is a quick solution to the tricky
challenge of bringing together two very hot trends -- wireless and
Internet, which has opened the way into the future.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Business Times reported recently that more than 15
percent of handphones sold globally will be Net-ready this year
and by 2003 all handphones, PDAs and other pocket-sized electronic
devices are expected to access the Internet as a standard
functions.
</P>
<P>
Reports said wireless device users accessing the internet are
expected to increase a whopping 700 percent from 7.4 million in
1999 to 61.5 million by 2003 in the U.S. alone.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are seen seething across the world to get ready for
next e-wave: m-commerce which is e-commerce that is done over
mobile phones and other hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
Specialists have predicted that even before conventional e-
commerce can rise to its full potential, m-commerce will take the
central stage in the e-commerce businesses.
</P>
<P>
While some estimates have put global mobile related revenue at
10 billion U.S. dollars in 2003, Andersen Consulting projects
global m-commerce revenue to leap quadruple from 12.7 billion U.S.
dollars this year to 55.4 billion U.S. dollars in 2003 to 55.4
billion U.S. dollars by that year.
</P>
<P>
Fierce competition in wireless mobile sector looms large across
the world as world players are already at the starting blocks for
new e-wave race.
</P>
<P>
Oracle and Motorola have joined hands to form a venture that
seeks to cash in the explosive growth of wireless devices as well
as high evaluations now given to wireless business on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Paris-based Cap Gemini, one of the world's major
information technology providers, has launched its first multi-
million dollar global wireless Internet center in Asia and its
Singapore-based Asian-Pacific headquarters aims to become a
globally recognized center of excellence in developing key
technologies that enable mobile services and solutions based on
industry standard platform, .
</P>
<P>
It is clear that wireless "web" services will become a
dominant ecosystem in an increasingly networked and knowledge-
based society.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
