<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Use Biologic Method to Kill Cotton Aphid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have developed
a biologic method to prevent and kill cotton aphid so as to
guarantee cotton production and promote the development of animal
husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Ecological and Geological Research
Institute of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, affiliated with the
China Academy of Sciences, built belts of clover around the cotton
fields for the purpose to kill aphids.
</P>
<P>
Clover is the parasitic body for ladybugs and stink flies, both
are natural enemies of cotton aphids.
</P>
<P>
Cutting the clover at the time when the cotton aphids reach the
biggest number, the number of aphids is reduced by 97 percent from
70,000 to 2,000 head per mu (0.066 hectares), while the number of
ladybugs and stink flies increase by 19 times from 50 to almost 1,
000 head per mu.
</P>
<P>
As clover is also a kind of high-quality forage, large-scale
planting of clover has helped develop animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
If Xinjiang plants some 1.5 million mu (100,000 hectares) of
clover, or one-tenth of the total area of cotton fields, the
region can produce 1.5 million tons of dry forage and 1.5 billion
yuan (180 million U.S. dollars) of output value annually,
according to experts' calculation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Returned Students Devote to Nation's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Students returned from overseas
have made increasing contribution to social and economic
development in Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 enterprises have been established in Nanjing by
returned students, involving economic, scientific, technological
and educational sectors. A dozen of the enterprises are engaged in
electronics, information, and new materials and are expected to be
helpful to promoting local hi-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, Nanjing has had some 12,000 students studying
overseas and more than one-third of them have returned to the city
to pursue their career. More than 80 percent of the returned are
professors or associate professors. And 60 percent of them have
been awarded for research and development findings. Some 1,100
have even participated in the nation's major scientific and
technological research projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
