<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fulham to Launch pro Women's Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- English fist division football
club Fulham has announced it is to launch England's first
professional women's team - with a built-in maternity clause.
</P>
<P>
The club has offered fixed-term contracts to a number of women
which include a provision for time off to have a baby.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian international midfielder Margunn Haugenes has already
been lured to the club, owned by Harrods boss Mohamed al-Fayed.
</P>
<P>
When the team is complete, the number of squad members will top
16 and is expected to be up and running for the 2000/2001 season.
</P>
<P>
The women will train most weekday afternoons at the club's
Motspur Park ground and will receive similar benefits to the men's
First Team, including health insurance.
</P>
<P>
Club chairman al-Fayed said: "After seeing some of the Women's
World Cup competition last summer in America, I realized the
tremendous potential of women's football.
</P>
<P>
"It is my hope that Fulham Football Club can play a part in
building opportunities for women to play professional football in
this country and in time enhance its profile," he said.
</P>
<P>
Women's amateur teams have been raising their profile in recent
years, and the Women's FA Cup final is now televised.
</P>
<P>
Last year's winners Arsenal Ladies will surrender their title
this year to either legendary women's team Doncaster Belles or
1998
finalists Croydon.
</P>
<P>
The two teams contest the final on 1 May at Sheffield United's
Bramhall Lane ground.
</P>
<P>
Mick McGuire, assistant chief executive of The Professional
Footballers' Association, backed the move.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We have always supported ladies' football and are
happy to offer them exactly the same benefits and support as our
current members. We are keen to enhance what is already a growing
industry and we welcome them on board."
</P>
<P>
Kelly Simmons, the Football Association's women's game co-
ordinator, added: "We think it's fantastic that Fulham are taking
the lead and being the first club to support a women's
professional team. It ties in very nicely with the FA's strategy
to establish a women's professional league within the next three
years and we hope other clubs will look to Fulham and follow suit.
" 
</P>
</TEXT>
