<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President OKs Anti-Inflation Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
signed an anti-inflation document here on Friday, saying the
protracted high inflation is "the root cause for all evils and
discomfort in the country."
</P>
<P>
The document was prepared by Turkish Union of Chambers and
Commodities Exchanges (TOBB) and the Turkish Exporters' Assembly
(TIM) within the framework of their "Turkey is Defeating
Inflation " campaign, reported the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Demirel asserted that the anti-inflation struggle should be
above party politics, saying that no matter what party comes to
power, the Turkish people's No. 1 problem is always to cope with
the high cost of living.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the president said, all countries' economic
programs aim to raise lower-class people to middle class and lift
middle class to upper class.
</P>
<P>
However, inflation creates the opposite effect, destroying the
middle class and widening the class gap, he said, adding "inflation
enlarges the lower and upper classes."
</P>
<P>
According to the TOBB-TIM document signed by Demirel, Turkey can
hardly sustain its economic and social development with the
country's two-digital annual inflation rate continuing.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the government embarked on a three-year structural
adjustment and stabilization program, aimed primarily at curbing
chronic inflation while ensuring a sustainable growth in output.
</P>
<P>
The program envisages cutting the inflation rate to 10 percent
by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Economy Recep Onal said in his speech at the
signing ceremony that the momentum gained in the structural reform
will be resolutely and decisively maintained by the government.
</P>
<P>
However, he called on the people to give full support to the
government's anti-inflation program on a long-term basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
