<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Minister of Culture and
Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani on Thursday called on the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO) to help return antiquities of ancient countries, which
have been moved abroad due to war and occupation, to their "true
owners."
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani made the appeal at a ceremony organized by UNESCO to
award young Iranian artist Fatimah Sharifi who won a UNESCO prize
for her drawing of the local mosque of her native town Saveh, south
of Tehran, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He suggested establishing a cooperative link between museums of
different countries and swapping historical belongings, of which
there were duplicates, as presents. This, he said, could be a
measure to check the trend of smuggling.
</P>
<P>
"We should try to legalize purchasing those historical
belongings for which there exist duplicates and let the collectors
sell their collections to others," he said. 
