<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes Russia's Ratification of Nuclear Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told a briefing that Russia'
s ratification of the treaty is "an important step. We welcome
that. "
</P>
<P>
Lockhart and State Department spokesman James Rubin both
defended the U.S. "leadership" in arms control although the treaty
was rejected by the U.S. Senate last year.
</P>
<P>
"I think that we work very closely around the world, and the
United States' leadership on arms control, nonproliferation is
unparalleled, and we look forward to working with the new Russian
government on a whole series of arms control issues," Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said it is the U.S. efforts that led to the signing of
the CTBT. "It was the United States that led the way in signing
the comprehensive test ban and pushing for its negotiation and
ultimately its agreement. So I think we feel quite confident that
it was our leadership that helped," Rubin told a briefing at the
State Department.
</P>
<P>
Both Rubin and Lockhart stressed that the U.S. government will
continue its efforts to persuade the Senate to ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that as time goes on and we are able to make our case
to the Senate, our Senate will follow the lead of many other
countries around the world and ratify an important treaty,"
Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rubin told reporters that the government has appointed retired
Gen. John Shalikashvili, a former chairman of the joint chiefs of
staff, to oversee a campaign to win over U.S. senators to support
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"It is so important that we need to begin to have some quiet
consultations with senators who have legitimate questions and
concerns that we think can be addressed, so that we can soon
enough ratify the comprehensive test ban," said Rubin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
