<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Indians Oppose Celebration of Discovery (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The representatives of the indigenous ethnic groups will
demonstrate Saturday in Corona Vermelha, in the state of Bahia,
where Franciscan monk Henrique de Coimbra celebrated the first
mass on Brazilian soil 500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese navigator Pedro Alvares Cabral arrived in Brazil on
April 22, 1500.
</P>
<P>
The Indians say they have nothing to commemorate about and will
demonstrate against the lack of governmental attention to their
problems, especially the demarcation of their territories.
</P>
<P>
The Indians and the members of the Landless Movement will march
toward Porto Seguro, where the official events to remember the
date will be held, to be attended by Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and his Portuguese counterpart Jorge Sampaio.
Corona Vermelha is 22 kilometers away of Porto Seguro.
</P>
<P>
In Brazil, a country with over 8.5 million square kilometers of
soil, 90 percent of the land is in the hands of 20 percent of the
people, while the poorest 40 percent own just 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 people -- 2,000 Indians and 3,000 Landless Movement
members -- went to Corona Vermelha to take part in the Indigenous
Conference, supported by representatives of the Negro Movement,
labor unions, and popular organizations.
</P>
<P>
The urgent demarcation of their lands is the most outstanding
claim of the indigenous people, because their terrains are invaded
by mining and lumber firms and rural landholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Indians Oppose Celebration of Discovery (2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The authorities deployed 5,000 military and civilian policemen
to bar the demonstrators from entering the commemoration areas,
and placed ten police fences in the main entrances of the city of
Porto Seguro.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government plans to exalt the history of the
country with the commemoration of the 500 years of the discovery,
but the indigenous people's protests will tarnish the
commemorative events.
</P>
<P>
According to historians, when Pedro Alvares Cabral arrived in
Brazil at the head of a Portuguese expedition, the territory had
five million indigenous people, most of whom were assassinated by
the Portuguese colonizers.
</P>
<P>
The last official statistics put the indigenous population at
350,000 people.
</P>
<P>
It can be understood that the indigenous peoples do not want to
commemorate the anniversary of the discovery, a tragedy for their
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
"If anyone should commemorate it's the Portuguese. They
discovered, colonized and plundered" Brazil, said Kebengele
Munanga of the Center for African Studies at the University of Sao
Paulo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Considers Too Demanding Economic Plan for Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- International Monetary Fund (IMF)
acting director Stanley Fisher said Friday that the economic plan
agreed on between the institution and Ecuador is "very demanding."
</P>
<P>
The plan "will affect all the people" and has as a goal the
protection of the poor, Fisher told the Ecuadoran press from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
The IMF approved Wednesday an agreement with Ecuador for an
economic program that includes a 304 million dollar contingency
credit and a bimonthly vigilance of the country's finances.
</P>
<P>
"If the program is successful, it will be very important for
the future of Ecuador, but it is necessary for the political
system to act in a coordinated way," said Fisher.
</P>
<P>
"Whether Ecuador can or cannot fulfill his part of the
agreement is a question that must be addressed to Ecuador, to its
society, and to its congress," said the IMF director.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement is done and to comply with it or not is a
question the Ecuadoran government must answer," said Fisher.
</P>
<P>
According to Fisher, the IMF examined with the Ecuadoran
government a calendar of adjustments, but its application is a
sovereign decision of the South American country.
</P>
<P>
The application of the adjustments responds to a macroeconomics
necessity, said Fisher, speaking highly of the seriousness of the
government of President Gustavo Noboa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Refuses to Set Timetable for Reuniting Elian, Father </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After the 15-minute meeting at the Justice Department with Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, Reno said in a short statement that she told him
that "I could not commit to a particular course of action or
timetable."
</P>
<P>
"I was deeply moved by Mr. Gonzalez' evident love for his son...
I assured him I would continue working toward the goal of
reuniting him with his child," Reno said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Reno said the father expressed great concern for and requested
a quick reunion with the boy, who has been here for nearly five
months since he survived in the Atlantic sea off Florida. The boy
's mother and 10 others were all drowned.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place as Reno, having exhausted almost all
options, was waiting for her law enforcement officials to
determine how to make the boy transferred to his father.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton said Thursday that the six-year-old Cuban
shipwreck survivor, Elian Gonzalez, should be promptly and orderly
reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters at the White House that there is "no
conceivable argument" to keep Elian and his father apart after a
federal appeals court ruled the boy cannot leave the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I think he should be reunited with his son. That is the law
and the main argument of the family in Miami for not doing so has
now been removed," Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
asked Americans to write to Clinton and Attorney General Janet
Reno to pressure them to reunite him with Elian.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta
issued an order that keeps Elian in the United States pending an
appeal for an asylum filed by the relatives in Miami for the boy.
</P>
</TEXT>
