<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15,000 Russians Die of Clearing Up Chernobyl Disaster Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Over 15,000 Russians, involved in
the clearing operation following the 1986 Chernobyl disaster in
Ukraine, have died of nuclear radiation, Chernobyl league
president Vyacheslav Grishin told a news conference in Moscow
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Another 50,000 people have become invalids, most of whom are
just 38-48 years old, and the number of invalids among people
involved in the clearing operation has increased nearly 12 folds
since 1991, he said.
</P>
<P>
The area polluted with over one curie/square kilometer of
cesium-137 totals 57,000 square meters. More than 52,000 out of 91,
000 people living in 267 villages near the accident scene have
left the polluted area, which was to become totally uninhabited,
but 8,400 families are still living there.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen years after the disaster, the content of cesium-137 in
timber, the flesh of wild animals, mushrooms and berries in the
polluted area shows no signs of receding, Grishin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
