<HEADLINE> Erekat Demands Israel to Return All Captured Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel must return all the
land it captured during the 1967 Middle East War for a future
Palestinian state, Palestinian top negotiator Saed Erekat said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There is going to be a Palestinian state along the June 4,
1967, boundaries, with East Jerusalem as its capital next to
Israel," said Erekat, who was accompanying Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to Washington for a meeting with President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a news conference in Washington, in
which he also said Arafat was still in Washington after his
meeting with Clinton on Thursday and holding talks with
Palestinian colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Territorial concessions that Israel is prepared to make are far
more modest than those foreseen by Erekat. On Thursday, the State
Department said agreement is possible only if both sides are
prepared to settle for less than their maximum demands.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that given the differences with Israel on
territorial and other issues, a new round of negotiations,
scheduled on April 30 - May 12, "is not going to be an easy
process."
</P>
<P>
He also cautioned Israel against renewed settlement activity,
saying: "We should work in an atmosphere devoid of any unilateral
steps, and unilateral actions that may reflect negatively on the
atmosphere required to achieve agreement."
</P>
<P>
Hassan Abdel Rahman, the Palestine Liberation Organization
representative in Washington, said U.N. Security Council
Resolution 242 will be the basis for Palestinian territorial
demands.
</P>
<P>
The resolution requires Israel to withdraw from occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
Rahman said agreements with Israel specify clearly the coming
negotiations should lead to implementation of 242. 
</P>
</TEXT>
