<HEADLINE> Nigerian Telecom Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government on Friday
announced the compulsory retirement of four executive directors
and 17 general managers in a major shake-up of Nigerian
Telecommunications Corporation (NITEL).
</P>
<P>
Earmarked for privatization along with several other state-run
 inefficient and graft-ridden utilities, NITEL is a major revenue
earner for the country, perhaps next to oil and the customs
service.
</P>
<P>
But it is widely criticized for failure to provide a reliable
telephone service in Africa's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
As part of ongoing efforts by the 11-month-old government of
President Olusegun Obasanjo to rid state-run parastatals of
corruption and inefficiency, a number of chief executives have
been fired.
</P>
<P>
But the recent sacking of the entire management of Nigerian
Power Authority has had little effect on the erratic power supply
in the oil-rich nation.  
</P>
