<DOCNO> XIE20000421.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E-Commerce in Asia-Pacific to Reach 1.6 Trln Dlrs in 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Buoyed by a combination of
regional strength, an American market research firm predicted this
week that e-commerce in Asia-Pacific will surge to 1.6 trillion U.
S. dollars in 2004.
</P>
<P>
According to Forrester Research, the region's countries will
benefit from local e-commerce development efforts and tight links
to international supply chains in a number of key industries.
</P>
<P>
These factors will make Asia-Pacific an important player in the
global Internet economy, which Forrester estimates will reach 6.9
trillion dollars in 2004.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the advantages that will accelerate the region's e-
commerce development, Forrester mentioned pressure from global
trading partners, falling trade barriers and government enthusiasm
for e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
Deep links to global supply chains will accelerate the region's
adoption of e-commerce as industry leaders pull their trading
partners online, Forrester said, citing Singapore as an example.
The country's 86 percent exports to the United States are sold
into the computing and electronics industries at the leading edge
of online business trade. Meanwhile, the research firm said,
national commitments to infrastructure development and economic
growth will create new opportunities throughout the region. The
resulting e-commerce gains will be tightly linked to business-to-
business (B2B) trade in Asia-Pacific, with more than 1.5 trillion
dollars of the region's total online sales linked to B2B sector.
</P>
<P>
However, Forrester said, e-commerce will not develop uniformly
across the region. According to the firm, online trade requires
public policy support, including low barriers to trade, stable
currencies and flexible capital markets, as well as a technology
infrastructure to reach its full potential.
</P>
<P>
These contributing factors are not equally present in the
region, Forrester said. In Hong Kong, for instance, low trade
barriers are accelerating online trade, while India's substantial
tariffs are delaying its development. Meanwhile, China's role in
the Internet economy will be hindered by its weak infrastructure.
"This disparity will make Asia-Pacific one of the last regions to
reach full e-commerce maturity," Forrester said.
</P>
<P>
Forrester estimates that e-commerce will account for 8.6
percent of worldwide sales of goods and services in 2004. The
expansion of online trade, however, will be highly concentrated,
with 12 countries representing nearly 85 percent of worldwide Net
sales.
</P>
<P>
According to Forrester's forecast, the U.S. will continue to be
the global e-commerce leader with online sales reaching 3.2
trillion dollars in 2004. Western Europe will hit 1.5 trillion
dollars with stronger business-to-consumer (B2C) sales than Asia-
Pacific. Plagued by infrastructure deficiencies, e-commerce will
reach 82 billion dollars in Latin America, while Eastern Europe,
Africa and the Middle East will contribute a combined 68.6 billion
dollars in 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
