<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smaller, Entrepreneurial Firms Lure American Accounting Graduates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A new survey released Friday
suggests that the growth of high-tech industry and the enticement
of smaller, entrepreneurial firms have shifted an old trend in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
A generation ago, most American accounting and finance
graduates sought jobs at large public accounting firms or major
corporations. Now small to mid-sized companies rank first among
the most desired business environments, according to a new poll of
chief financial officers (CFOs).
</P>
<P>
The survey was developed by Accountemps, the largest U.S.
temporary staffing service for accounting, finance and bookkeeping
professionals. About 1,400 CFOs of U.S. companies with more than
20 employees were asked to identify the most attractive employment
environment among today's accounting graduates.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-five CFOs surveyed identified small to mid-sized
companies, compared to 22 percent of them who considered large
corporations. Of the rest of the CFOs, 13 percent and 11 percent
respectively picked up small to mid-sized public accounting firms
and large public accounting firms.
</P>
<P>
"The career opportunities with rapidly growing small to mid-
sized companies are enticing, particularly the promise of having
an equity stake in the business," said Accountemps, analyzing the
results. "In addition, smaller firms are the ideal training ground
for hands-on experience with a variety of business functions."
</P>
<P>
Start-up companies were perceived as the least attractive
employment option by CFOs at firms of all sizes, as only 7 percent
selected them as the most attractive.
</P>
<P>
"Small yet established businesses offer an entrepreneurial,
fast-growth environment with fewer of the risks associated with an
untested venture, " Accountemps said.
</P>
<P>
CFOs at the largest companies with 500 or more employees in the
survey viewed jobs with the Big Five as most appealing. "A
position with a large public firm has been the traditional first
step in an accountant's career," the firm said. ""It's likely that
the finance executives surveyed at large corporations began their
own careers this way." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
